{"pageid": 2, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab8", "text": "Let [mathjaxinline]f(t) = \\begin{cases} 1 & 0 < t < 1\\\\\\ 0 & -1 < t < 0 \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline] be the function of period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline].  ![A 2 periodic function equal to 0 on the intervals from -1 to 0, from 1 to 2, and equal to 1 on the intervals from -2 to 1 and 0 to 1.](/static/images/u6_step_periodic.svg)  In the previous lecture, we found that the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin (n\\pi t)}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 8.1** Find the system response to  [mathjax]\\ddot x + 10^2 x = f(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      On the previous page, we found that the particular solution for a differential equation of this type will take the form  [mathjax]\\boxed {\\displaystyle x_p(t) =\\frac{a_0}{2\\omega _0^2} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} \\frac{a_n \\cos \\omega _n t}{\\omega _0^2-\\omega _n^2} + \\frac{b_n \\sin \\omega _n t}{\\omega _0^2-\\omega _n^2} }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, in this example, the particular solution is given by  [mathjax]x_p = \\frac{1}{200} + \\frac{2}{\\pi } \\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin (n\\pi t)}{(100-(n\\pi )^2)n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Near resonance", "filename": "solveodes-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Near resonance"}

{"pageid": 4, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab12", "text": "**Other boundary conditions**  Besides the two simple boundary conditions we described above, there are a few others that can be useful. One other boundary condition, not used as often but still important, is what is know as the **Robin** boundary condition. This condition has the form on the boundary  [mathjax]u + a\\frac{\\partial u }{\\partial x} = b[/mathjax]| (4.28)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are constants. Such a condition is usually used to represent some sort of convective transport occurring at the boundaries. Imagine a glass of beer or soda with the top open to the atmosphere, and a wind is blowing over it. [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] naturally diffuses into the air above the beverage, and the wind will tend to carry it away. The above boundary condition deals with this case.  Other boundary conditions", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab12-text3.html", "title": "Other boundary conditions"}

{"pageid": 9, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab3", "text": "The square wave of height [mathjaxinline]\\pi /4[/mathjaxinline], which we denote by [mathjaxinline]S(t) = \\frac{\\pi }{4}\\mathrm{Sq}(t)[/mathjaxinline] has Fourier series  [mathjax]S\\left(t\\right) \\, = \\, \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}\\left(t\\right) = \\sin t + \\frac{1}{3} \\sin 3t + \\frac{1}{5} \\sin 5t + \\cdots \\\\\\ \\, = \\, \\sum _{n \\text{ odd}}^{\\infty } \\frac{1}{n} \\sin nt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that the discontinuities are at the integer multiples of [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  You can visualize the sum of the first few terms of this Fourier series using the mathlet below. The partial sum  [mathjax]b_1 \\sin t + \\dotsb + b_{11} \\sin 11t[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is displayed in blue. (Initially these coefficients are all zero, so the display shows a horizontal blue line. )    * Choose the radio button for **Target A** to see the graph of [mathjaxinline]S(t)[/mathjaxinline].     * We know that the function is odd, so all the [mathjaxinline]a_n=0[/mathjaxinline]. Thus we represent this as a **Sine series** .     * We know that the coefficients [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] involve only odd terms, so we can also select the radio button **Odd terms** .   Use the sliders to select the coefficients [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]S(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Observe how each successive [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] creates a better and better approximation to [mathjaxinline]S(t)[/mathjaxinline].  Activity", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Activity"}

{"pageid": 10, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab4", "text": "Because  [mathjax]\\sin (t+2\\pi ) = \\sin t, \\quad \\cos (t+2\\pi ) = \\cos t, \\quad[/mathjax]|   ---|---      hold for all [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\,[/mathjaxinline], the functions [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin t \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos t \\,[/mathjaxinline] are called periodic with period [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi \\,[/mathjaxinline]. In general a function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] defined for all real [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\,[/mathjaxinline] is **periodic of period [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline]** if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t+P) = f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  There are many such functions beyond the sinusoidal functions. To construct one, divide the real line into intervals of length [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline], start with any function defined on one such interval [mathjaxinline]\\, [t_0,t_0+P) \\,[/mathjaxinline], and then copy its values in the other intervals. The entire graph consists of horizontally shifted copies of the width [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] graph.  ![See caption](/static/images/u6_periodic_P.svg)    **Figure 1** : A periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] created by copying   and shifting the graph over the interval [mathjaxinline][t_0, t_0+P)[/mathjaxinline].      For now we focus on functions with period [mathjaxinline]\\, P=2\\pi \\,[/mathjaxinline], which are defined over the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, [-\\pi ,\\pi ) \\,[/mathjaxinline].  **Question 4.1** Is [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin 3t \\,[/mathjaxinline] periodic of period [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi \\,[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer  The **shortest** period is [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi /3 \\,[/mathjaxinline], but [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin 3t \\,[/mathjaxinline] is also periodic with period any positive integer multiple of [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi /3 \\,[/mathjaxinline], including [mathjaxinline]\\, 3(2\\pi /3)=2\\pi \\,[/mathjaxinline]: [mathjax]\\sin (3(t+2\\pi )) = \\sin (3t+6\\pi ) = \\sin 3t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   So the answer is yes.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Periodic functions", "filename": "introtofourier-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Periodic functions"}

{"pageid": 12, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab9", "text": "Steps for solving  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad 0< x < L, \\, \\, t>0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with given boundary conditions and initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)=f(x)[/mathjaxinline].    1. Ignore initial condition and focus on boundary conditions.     2. If any boundary condition is nonzero, find a steady state solution [mathjaxinline]\\Theta (x)[/mathjaxinline] which satisfies the given boundary conditions. Reduce problem to solving [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h(x,t) = \\theta (x,t)-\\Theta (x)[/mathjaxinline] which has homogeneous boundary conditions and initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h(x,0) = f(x)-\\Theta (x)[/mathjaxinline].     3. Look up standard form of eigenvalues, eigenfunctions, and normal modes for the homogeneous cases already computed.   Else, use separation of variables. That is, try [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h(x,t)=v(x)w(t)[/mathjaxinline] (or [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)=v(x)w(t)[/mathjaxinline] if original problem is homogeneous) to find family of normal modes [mathjaxinline]\\theta _n(x,t) = v_n(x)w_n(t)[/mathjaxinline].    4. Take linear combinations to get the general solution   [mathjax]\\boxed {\\theta _h(x,t) = b_1 w_1(t) v_1(x) + b_2 w_2(t) v_2(x) + b_3 w_3(t) v_3(x) + \\cdots }[/mathjax]|   ---|---     5. Extend the initial condition [mathjaxinline]f(x)-\\Theta (x)[/mathjaxinline] to have the correct base period and even/odd properties in order to be able to solve for the Fourier coefficients   [mathjax]f(x)-\\Theta (x) = b_1 v_1(x) + b_2 v_2(x) + b_3 v_3(x) + \\cdots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---    Steps of procedure", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Steps of procedure"}

{"pageid": 13, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab6", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] are vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\mathbf v\\cdot \\mathbf{w}\\colon =\\sum _{k=1}^n v_k w_k,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]v_k[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w_k[/mathjaxinline] are the [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline]th components of the vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] respectively. Can one define the dot product of two functions? Sort of.  If we think of vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] as functions from the finite sets  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v: \\left\\\\{ -\\pi + 2\\pi /n, -\\pi + 4\\pi /n, \\dotsc , -\\pi + 2n\\pi /n =\\pi \\right\\\\}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{w}: \\left\\\\{ -\\pi + 2\\pi /n, -\\pi + 4\\pi /n, \\dotsc , -\\pi + 2n\\pi /n =\\pi \\right\\\\}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbb {R},[/mathjaxinline] |  |      then the inner product of these functions can be written as [mathjaxinline]\\langle \\mathbf v, \\mathbf{w}\\rangle[/mathjaxinline], where  [mathjax]\\langle \\mathbf v, \\mathbf{w}\\rangle = \\sum _{k=1}^{n} \\mathbf v(-\\pi + 2k\\pi /n)\\mathbf{w}(-\\pi + 2k\\pi /n).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      When we take the continuous limit as [mathjaxinline]n\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] become continuous, real valued functions defined on [mathjaxinline](-\\pi , \\pi ][/mathjaxinline], and then the infinite sum becomes an integral.  **Definition 6.1** If [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] are real-valued periodic functions with period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], then we will define their **inner product** as  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\langle u(t),v(t) \\rangle }} \\colon =\\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi u(t) v(t) \\, dt[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is the continuous analogue of the dot product for vectors. ( _Sometimes the inner product is defined on different intervals for functions with different periods. In other definitions, for convenience there is a constant multiplier, which is a normalizing factor._ )  **Definition 6.2** We say that two [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic functions [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] are **orthogonal** if  [mathjax]\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } u(t)v(t)\\, dt = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 6.3** For example,  [mathjax]\\langle 1, \\cos t \\rangle = \\displaystyle \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi \\cos t \\, dt = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus the functions [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos t[/mathjaxinline] are orthogonal.  A dot product for functions", "filename": "introtofourier-tab6-text1.html", "title": "A dot product for functions"}

{"pageid": 14, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab3", "text": "To explain the Heat Equation, we start with a thought experiment. If we fix the temperature at the ends, [mathjaxinline]\\theta (0,t) = 0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta (L,t) = T[/mathjaxinline], what will happen in the long term as [mathjaxinline]t \\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline]? Assume for the moment that there is a steady state. That is, that [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] converges to some temperature profile [mathjaxinline]\\Theta (x)[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) \\to \\Theta (x), \\quad t \\to \\infty .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The answer is that  [mathjax]\\Theta (x) = \\frac{T}{L} x \\quad (\\text{linear}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (L/2,t)[/mathjaxinline] at the midpoint [mathjaxinline]L/2[/mathjaxinline] tends to the average of [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline], namely [mathjaxinline]T/2[/mathjaxinline]. At the point [mathjaxinline]L/4[/mathjaxinline], halfway between [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]L/2[/mathjaxinline], the temperature tends to the average of the temperature at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]T/2[/mathjaxinline], and so forth.  At a very small scale, this same mechanism, the tendency of the temperature profile toward a straight line equilibrium means that if [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is concave down then the temperature in the middle should decrease (so the profile becomes closer to being straight). If [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is concave up, then the temperature in the middle should increase (so that, once again, the profile becomes closer to being straight). We write this as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{ \\partial x^2} < 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\implies \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{ \\partial t} < 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{ \\partial x^2} > 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\implies \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{ \\partial t} > 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The simplest relationship that reflects this is a linear (proportional) relationship,  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{ \\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{ \\partial x^2}, \\quad \\nu >0 .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Fourier introduced the Heat Equation, solved it, and confirmed in many cases that it predicts correctly the behavior of temperature in experiments like the one with the metal bar.  Actually, Fourier crushed the problem, figuring out the whole formula for [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] and not just when the initial value is [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)=1[/mathjaxinline], but also when the initial temperature varies with [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. His formula even predicts accurately what happens when [mathjaxinline]0< t< \\tau[/mathjaxinline].  _If you are interested you can click below to see a scale model derivation of the Heat Equation._  ###  Another derivation (optional)  We are going to look at one way to derive a partial differential equation describing the evolution of temperature in an insulated, uniform bar of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline]. We first looked at this problem in the course _Linear Algebra and NxN Systems of Differential equations_ , when we were studying [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] systems. Initially, we considered a rod of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline], with two thermometers placed evenly along its length, at the points [mathjaxinline]x_1 = L/3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2 = 2L/3[/mathjaxinline]. The left end of the rod was held at the temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta _L[/mathjaxinline] and the right end was held at [mathjaxinline]\\theta _R[/mathjaxinline]. We used _Newton's law of cooling_ , which said that the rate of change of temperature at [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d\\theta _1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] is affected by the adjacent temperatures [mathjaxinline]\\theta _L[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _2[/mathjaxinline].The left contribution is proportional to the difference in temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta _L-\\theta _1[/mathjaxinline], while the right contribution is proportional to [mathjaxinline]\\theta _2-\\theta _1[/mathjaxinline]. This meant that we could write down a system of two equations for [mathjaxinline]\\theta _1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _2[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta _1}{dt} = k(\\theta _L-\\theta _1) + k (\\theta _2-\\theta _1)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = k (\\theta _L-2\\theta _1+\\theta _2)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.1)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta _2}{dt} = k(\\theta _1-\\theta _2) + k (\\theta _R-\\theta _2)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = k(\\theta _1-2\\theta _2+\\theta _R).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.2)      We were a little careless when we first looked at this system. Looking more carefully, we can see that if we want to place many thermometers on the bar and track the interaction of temperatures at many points, then we should adjust the constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] for the distance between points. Let's suppose that we place [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] thermometers at points [mathjaxinline]x_n = n\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]n = 1, \\dots , N[/mathjaxinline], equally spaced along the bar, with [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\frac{L}{N+1}[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]\\theta _n(t)[/mathjaxinline] is the temperature at [mathjaxinline]x_n[/mathjaxinline], then the correct scaling for the influence of [mathjaxinline]\\theta _{n+1}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _{n-1}[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline]\\theta _n[/mathjaxinline] is the following version of Newton's law:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta _n}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\nu \\frac{(\\theta _{n-1}-\\theta _n)}{(\\Delta x)^2} - \\nu \\frac{(\\theta _{n}-\\theta _{n+1})}{(\\Delta x)^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.3)   ---|---|---|---|---      In other words, [mathjaxinline]k = \\nu /(\\Delta x)^2[/mathjaxinline] is the appropriate scaling for [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline] a property of the material. (This inverse square law is what Fourier discovered by testing bars of metal of various lengths. He then applied the insight that calculus brings, namely that the same rule should work at infinitesimal scales.) We can now simplify the right hand side to obtain  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta _n}{dt} = \\nu \\frac{(\\theta _{n+1}-2\\theta _n+\\theta _{n-1})}{(\\Delta x)^2}. [/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.4)   ---|---|---|---      We want to consider the limit [mathjaxinline]N\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline] so that [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x\\to 0[/mathjaxinline]. We are interested in deriving a partial differential equation for the temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] at any position [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] along the bar. We therefore need to choose [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] so that [mathjaxinline]x_n \\to x[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]N\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. A possible choice is [mathjaxinline]n = \\left\\lfloor {x/\\Delta x}\\right\\rfloor = \\left\\lfloor {x(N+1)/L}\\right\\rfloor[/mathjaxinline]. As [mathjaxinline]N\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline], the right hand side of the equation for [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta _n}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] becomes [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}(x)[/mathjaxinline]. In this limit, we have the following partial differential equation describing the continuous evolution of temperature in the bar:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.5)   ---|---|---|---      This is the heat equation.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The heat equation does not determine the solution completely by itself. We also need to specify what are known as **boundary conditions** and **initial conditions** .  **Boundary conditions** are the temperatures at the two ends of the rod at each time. For example, we can impose the boundary conditions that temperature is fixed for all time on the left and right sides at given temperatures:  [mathjax]\\theta (0,t) = \\theta _L, \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\theta (L ,t) = \\theta _R.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **The initial condition** can be any smooth function [mathjaxinline]\\theta _0(x)[/mathjaxinline] so that  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t=0) = \\theta _0(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As we shall see later, the boundary conditions and initial conditions together with the heat equation determine a **unique** temperature profile [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] for all future times [mathjaxinline]t > 0[/mathjaxinline].  Deriving the Heat Equation", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Deriving the Heat Equation"}

{"pageid": 15, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab2", "text": "Recall that for any function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] that is periodic and has period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], the Fourier series is given by  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty }\\left( a_n \\cos nt + b_n \\sin nt \\right),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the formulas for the coefficients [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] are given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\cos (nt)\\, dt,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\sin (nt)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |      By virtue of the fact that we have formulas for the coefficients, a function has only one Fourier series. That is, if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) = g(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline], then the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the same as the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]\\, g(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline].  We will use this idea to come up with easier ways to compute Fourier series.  Here are the Fourier series of some [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic functions.  **Name**|  **Function**|  **Fourier series**|  **Graph**   ---|---|---|---   Square wave |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\begin{cases} 1 & 0 < t < \\pi \\\\\\ -1 & -\\pi < t < 0 \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin (nt)}{n}[/mathjaxinline] | ![Square wave of period 2pi](/static/images/u6_squarewave_smaller.svg)   Sawtooth wave |  [mathjaxinline]W(t) = t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < t < \\pi[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle W(t) = 2\\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } \\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline] | ![Sawtooth wave of period 2pi](/static/images/u6_sawtooth_smaller.svg)   Triangle wave |  [mathjaxinline]T(t) = |t|[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < t< \\pi[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle T(t) = \\frac{\\pi }{2} - \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\cos (nt)}{n^2}[/mathjaxinline] | ![Triangle wave of period 2pi](/static/images/u6_twave_smaller.svg)  Uniqueness", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Uniqueness"}

{"pageid": 16, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab10", "text": "We have looked at extremely simple ideas coming from wired telephones and AM radios, as well as thinking about using an RLC circuit to filter signals. You can imagine that the world we live in is far more complicated. The circuits involved in your cell phone to filter out all kinds of different signals \u2014 wireless internet, cellular data, and GPS for example \u2014 are much more complicated than a simple RLC circuit. But nonetheless, the underlying principles are the same.  All of the exercises you've done so far involve using the Discrete Fourier Transform to study sound signals coming from musical instruments and voices playing a single note. These signals did not change much in time. However, we interact daily with speak recognition software that is able to process sound signals in real time fairly accurately (using machine learning algorithms among other things). To begin to do such a thing, you have to allow that your signals are changing in time. **Spectrograms** are a visual way of interpreting the Discrete Fourier Transform of signals that change in time.  Practical practice", "filename": "DFTLab-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Practical practice"}

{"pageid": 17, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab5", "text": "A linear combination like [mathjaxinline]2 \\sin 3t - 4 \\sin 7t[/mathjaxinline] is another periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  ![ ](/static/images/periodic-function.svg)    **Figure 2** : [mathjaxinline]2 \\sin 3t - 4 \\sin 7t[/mathjaxinline]   **Definition 5.1** A **Fourier series** is a linear combination of the infinitely many functions [mathjaxinline]\\cos nt[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] ranges over integers:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_0}{2} + a_1 \\cos t + a_2 \\cos 2t + a_3 \\cos 3t + \\cdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\quad \\quad + b_1 \\sin t + b_2 \\sin 2t + b_3 \\sin 3t + \\cdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (Terms like [mathjaxinline]\\cos (-2t)[/mathjaxinline] are redundant since [mathjaxinline]\\cos (-2t) = \\cos 2t[/mathjaxinline]. Also [mathjaxinline]\\sin 0t = 0[/mathjaxinline] produces nothing new. But [mathjaxinline]\\cos 0t = 1[/mathjaxinline] is included. We'll explain later why we write the first coefficient as [mathjaxinline]a_0[/mathjaxinline] divided by [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] instead of [mathjaxinline]a_0[/mathjaxinline].)  Written using sigma-notation:  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty a_n \\cos nt + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty b_n \\sin nt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 5.2** Recall that, for example, [mathjaxinline]g(t) = \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty b_n \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] means the sum of the series whose [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] term is obtained by plugging in the positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] into the expression [mathjaxinline]b_n \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline], so  [mathjax]g(t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin nt = b_1 \\sin t + b_2 \\sin 2t + b_3 \\sin 3t + \\cdots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In particular, at [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]g(0) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin (n0) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\cdot 0 = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 5.3** If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } a_n \\cos (nt)[/mathjaxinline], then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(\\pi )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } a_n \\cos (n\\pi )[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } a_n (-1)^n[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_0}{2} -a_1 + a_2 - a_3 + \\dotsb .[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Any Fourier series as above is periodic of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. _(Later we'll extend to the definition of Fourier series to include functions of other periods.)_    * The numbers [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] are called the **Fourier coefficients** of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline].     * Each summand ([mathjaxinline]\\, a_0/2 \\,[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\, a_n \\cos nt \\,[/mathjaxinline], or [mathjaxinline]\\, b_n \\sin nt \\,[/mathjaxinline]) is called a **Fourier component** of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline].   **Example 5.4** Define  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) \\colon =\\begin{cases} 1, & \\textrm{ if } 0<t<\\pi , \\\\\\ -1 & \\textrm{ if } -\\pi <t<0\\. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and extend it to a periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], called a **square wave** .  The function [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}(t)[/mathjaxinline] has jump discontinuities, for example at [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline]. The graph is usually drawn with vertical segments at the jumps (even though this violates the vertical line test).  ![ ](/static/images/u6_squarewave.svg)    **Figure 3** : The [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic square wave.      It turns out that  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\left( \\sin t + \\frac{\\sin 3t}{3} + \\frac{\\sin 5t}{5} + \\cdots \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We'll explain later today where this comes from.  Fourier series", "filename": "introtofourier-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Fourier series"}

{"pageid": 18, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab1", "text": "### Objectives:    * Apply **Fourier series methods** to solve LTI differential equations with general periodic input signals.     * Describe the system response to a **general periodic input signal** in terms of a **Fourier series** .     * Use **resonance** to determine the **dominant Fourier coefficients** in a system response to an input signal described as a Fourier series.     * Think of **sound** as a superposition of sine waves, and understand the ears ability to pick out Fourier coefficients, rather than hearing the superposition of the waves as one object.   Objectives", "filename": "solveodes-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 19, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab10", "text": "Here we provide the full computation of the Fourier series for the square wave of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) \\colon =\\begin{cases} 1, & \\textrm{ if } 0<t<\\pi , \\\\\\ -1 & \\textrm{ if } -\\pi <t<0\\. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![The 2 pi periodic square wave](/static/images/u6_squarewave.svg)  First we compute the constant term,  [mathjax]\\frac{a_0}{2} = \\frac{\\text{Signed area of one period}}{2\\pi } = \\frac{\\pi - \\pi }{2\\pi } = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Next we compute the rest of the Fourier coefficients [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]n>0[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\mathrm{Sq}(t)\\cos (nt)\\, dt \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( -\\int _{-\\pi }^{0} \\cos (nt)\\, dt + \\int _{0}^{\\pi } \\cos (nt)\\, dt \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( \\left. -\\frac{\\sin (nt)}{n} \\right|_{-\\pi }^{0} + \\left. \\frac{\\sin (nt)}{n} \\right|_{0}^{\\pi } \\right) \\, = \\, 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Finally, compute the coefficients [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\mathrm{Sq}(t)\\sin (nt)\\, dt \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( -\\int _{-\\pi }^{0} \\sin (nt)\\, dt + \\int _{0}^{\\pi } \\sin (nt)\\, dt \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( \\left. \\frac{\\cos (nt)}{n} \\right|_{-\\pi }^{0} - \\left. \\frac{\\cos (nt)}{n} \\right|_{0}^{\\pi } \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Note that [mathjaxinline]\\cos (n\\pi ) = \\cos (-n\\pi ) = (-1)^n[/mathjaxinline], therefore  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left( \\left. \\frac{\\cos (nt)}{n} \\right|_{-\\pi }^{0} - \\left. \\frac{\\cos (nt)}{n} \\right|_{0}^{\\pi } \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\left[ \\left( \\frac{1-(-1)^n}{n} \\right) - \\left( \\frac{(-1)^n-1}{n} \\right) \\right][/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\left( \\frac{1 - (-1)^n}{n}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{cases} \\frac{4}{n\\pi } & n \\text{ odd}, \\\\\\ 0 & n \\text{ even}.\\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore the Fourier series for the square wave is  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) \"=\" \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\left( \\sin t + \\frac{\\sin 3t}{3} + \\frac{\\sin 5t}{5} + \\cdots \\right) = \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}}^{\\infty } \\frac{ \\sin nt}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Video error  In the video above, the error is that the factor of [mathjaxinline]1/\\pi[/mathjaxinline] is missing.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Remark 10.1** Note that while the square wave was undefined at the jump discontinuities at every integer multiple of [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline], the Fourier series is well defined and is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] at each integer multiple of [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline] (because [mathjaxinline]\\sin (n\\pi ) = 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]).  Full computation", "filename": "introtofourier-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Full computation"}

{"pageid": 21, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab11", "text": "Find the Fourier series of the [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic function  [mathjax]f(t) = \\begin{cases} t & 0 < t < \\pi \\\\\\ 0 & -\\pi < t < 0 \\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:** In this example, we will work out the terms [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and leave it to you to find the coefficients [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline].  First, draw a picture.  ![The plot of the function in the problem statement](/static/images/u6_periodic_2pi_secondexample.svg)  Next, find the constant term:  [mathjax]\\frac{a_0}{2} =\\frac{1}{2\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\, dt =\\frac{\\text{area under one period of curve}}{\\text{length of period}} = \\frac{\\pi ^2/2}{2\\pi } = \\frac{\\pi }{4}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Now for the other terms [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle a_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\cos (nt)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{0}0\\cos (nt)\\, dt + \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{0}^{\\pi }t\\cos (nt)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{0}^{\\pi }t\\cos (nt)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Evaluating this integral, we find  [mathjax]\\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{0}^{\\pi }t\\cos (nt)\\, dt \\quad =\\quad \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\frac{\\cos (n\\pi )-1}{n^2} \\quad =\\quad \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\frac{(-1)^n-1}{n^2} \\quad =\\quad \\begin{cases} \\frac{-2}{\\pi n^2} & n \\text{ odd}\\\\\\ 0 & n \\text{ even}\\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore the Fourier series is given by  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{\\pi }{4} + \\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{-2}{\\pi n^2}\\cos (nt) + \\sum _{n} b_n \\sin (nt).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We leave the computation of the [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] as an exercise for you.  Find the Fourier series", "filename": "introtofourier-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Find the Fourier series"}

{"pageid": 23, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab7", "text": "In real life, there is always damping. {"pageid": 24, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab9", "text": "Define the step function  [mathjax]s(x) \\colon =\\begin{cases} 1, & \\text{ if } x<0 \\\\\\ 0, & \\text{ if } x>0, \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and consider the solution [mathjaxinline]u(x,t) = s(x-t)[/mathjaxinline] to the wave equation. {"pageid": 27, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab15", "text": "Find the Fourier series of the [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic **sawtooth** wave  [mathjax]f(t) = t, -\\pi < t < \\pi .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![ ](/static/images/u6_sawtooth.svg)    **Figure 5** : The sawtooth wave.       **Solution:** The function is odd, therefore [mathjaxinline]a_n=0[/mathjaxinline].  Using our simplified formula for [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline], we find  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\int _0^{\\pi } t\\sin (nt) \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\left[ \\left. \\frac{-t \\cos (nt)}{n}\\right|_{0}^{\\pi } - \\int _0^{\\pi } \\frac{-\\cos (nt)}{n}\\, dt \\right][/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\left[ -\\frac{\\pi (-1)^n}{n} + \\left. \\frac{\\sin (nt)}{n^2}\\right|_{0}^{\\pi } \\right][/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2(-1)^{n+1}}{n}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore the Fourier series for the sawtooth wave is  [mathjax]\\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } \\frac{2(-1)^{n+1}}{n}\\sin (nt).[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Saw tooth wave", "filename": "introtofourier-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Saw tooth wave"}

{"pageid": 29, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab12", "text": "Recall that for any function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] that is periodic and has period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], the Fourier series is given by  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty }\\left( a_n \\cos nt + b_n \\sin nt \\right),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the formulas for the coefficients [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] are given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_0}{2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t) \\, dt \\, =\\, \\frac{\\langle f(t), 1 \\rangle }{\\langle 1, 1 \\rangle },[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\cos (nt)\\, dt \\, =\\, \\frac{\\langle f(t), \\cos (nt)\\rangle }{\\langle \\cos nt, \\cos nt \\rangle }, \\qquad n\\geq 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi }\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f(t)\\sin (nt)\\, dt\\, =\\, \\frac{\\langle f(t), \\sin (nt)\\rangle }{\\langle \\sin nt, \\sin nt \\rangle }, \\qquad n\\geq 1.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      By virtue of the fact that we have formulas for the coefficients (in terms of an inner product on functions with respect to an orthogonal basis of functions), a function has only one Fourier series. That is, if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) = g(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline], then the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the same as the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]\\, g(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline].  We will use this idea to come up with easier ways to compute Fourier series.  Uniqueness", "filename": "introtofourier-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Uniqueness"}

{"pageid": 30, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab7", "text": "Boundary conditions that are not all zero are called **inhomogeneous boundary conditions.**  **Steps to solve a linear PDE with **inhomogeneous** boundary conditions:**    1. Find a particular solution [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p[/mathjaxinline] to the PDE with the inhomogeneous boundary conditions (but without initial conditions). If the boundary conditions do not depend on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], try to find the steady-state solution [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p(x)[/mathjaxinline], i.e., the solution that does not depend on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].     2. Then [mathjaxinline]\\theta \\colon =\\theta _p + \\theta _h[/mathjaxinline] is the general solution to the PDE with the inhomogeneous boundary conditions, where [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h[/mathjaxinline] is the general solution to the PDE with the homogeneous boundary conditions.     3. If initial conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)[/mathjaxinline] are given, use the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)-\\theta _p[/mathjaxinline] to find the specific solution to the PDE with the inhomogeneous boundary conditions. (This often involves finding Fourier coefficients.)   **Problem 7.1** Consider the same insulated uniform metal rod as before ([mathjaxinline]\\nu =1[/mathjaxinline], length [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline], initial temperature [mathjaxinline]1^{\\circ } \\mathrm{C}[/mathjaxinline]), but now suppose that the left end is held at [mathjaxinline]0^{\\circ } \\mathrm{C}[/mathjaxinline] while the right end is held at [mathjaxinline]20^{\\circ } \\mathrm{C}[/mathjaxinline]. Now what is [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:**    1. Forget the initial condition for now and look for a solution [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p=\\theta _p(x)[/mathjaxinline] that does not depend on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. Plugging this into the Heat Equation PDE gives [mathjaxinline]0 = \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}[/mathjaxinline]. The general solution to this simplified DE is [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p(x) = ax+b[/mathjaxinline] Imposing the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p(\\pi )=20[/mathjaxinline] leads to [mathjaxinline]b=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]a=20/\\pi[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p = \\frac{20}{\\pi } x[/mathjaxinline].     2. Write [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t) = \\theta _p(x)+\\theta _h(x,t)[/mathjaxinline]. Because our PDE is linear, and both [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _p(x)[/mathjaxinline] satisfy the heat equation, it follows that [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] also satisfies the heat equation   [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial t}\\theta _h(x,t) = \\frac{\\partial ^2}{\\partial x^2}\\theta _h(x,t) \\qquad 0 < x < \\pi .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Moreover, [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] has homogeneous boundary conditions  [mathjax]\\theta _h(0,t)=0, \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\theta _h(\\pi ,t)=0, \\qquad \\text{for } t>0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---     3. The PDE with the homogeneous boundary conditions is what we solved earlier; therefore the general solution for [mathjaxinline]\\theta _h[/mathjaxinline] is   [mathjax]\\theta _h = b_1 e^{-t} \\sin x + b_2 e^{-4t} \\sin 2x + b_3 e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\dotsb .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     4. The general solution to the PDE with inhomogeneous boundary conditions is   [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) = \\theta _p + \\theta _h = \\frac{20}{\\pi } x + b_1 e^{-t} \\sin x + b_2 e^{-4t} \\sin 2x + b_3 e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\dotsb .[/mathjax]| (4.8)   ---|---     5. To find the [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline], set [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] and use the initial condition on the left:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{20}{\\pi } x + b_1 \\sin x + b_2 \\sin 2x + b_3 \\sin 3x + \\cdots \\quad \\text{for all } x \\in (0,\\pi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.9)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1 - \\frac{20}{\\pi } x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_1 \\sin x + b_2 \\sin 2x + b_3 \\sin 3x + \\cdots \\quad \\text{for all } x \\in (0,\\pi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.10)      Extend [mathjaxinline]1 - \\frac{20}{\\pi } x[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline](0,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline] to an odd periodic function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. Then use the Fourier coefficient formulas to find the [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]f(x) = b_1 \\sin x + b_2 \\sin 2x + b_3 \\sin 3x + \\dotsb ;[/mathjax]|   ---|---      alternatively, find the Fourier series for the odd periodic extensions of [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] separately, and take a linear combination to get [mathjaxinline]1-\\frac{20}{\\pi }x[/mathjaxinline]. Once the [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] are found, plug them back into the general solution for the heat equation with inhomogeneous boundary conditions.  Solving the PDE with inhomogeneous boundary conditions", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Solving the PDE with inhomogeneous boundary conditions"}

{"pageid": 32, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab2", "text": "The exponential response formula (ERF) is a quick method for finding the response to any input that is expressible in terms of an exponential, sine, or cosine function. (We will review this method on the next page.) What happens when the input is not one of these?  If the input function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is periodic (of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]), we can express the function (where it is continuous) as an infinite sum of sines and cosines. This series representation is called a **Fourier series** :  [mathjax]f(t) = c_0+\\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty }\\left[ a_n \\cos (nt) + b_n \\sin (nt)\\right], \\qquad c_0, a_n, b_n \\text{ real constants}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ( _Note that here we are giving an expression that only works for [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi \\,[/mathjaxinline]-periodic functions. There is a formula that works more generally, which we will learn in the next lecture._ )  The benefit is, given an inhomogeneous linear differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)y = f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline], we can apply ERF to every term in the Fourier series.  **Input**|  | **Response**   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{b_n}} \\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\rightsquigarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{b_n}} y_n^{(s)}(t)[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{a_n}} \\cos (nt)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\rightsquigarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{a_n}} y_n^{(c)}(t)[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]c_0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\rightsquigarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline]      Taking the sum of all of the input terms we get an approximation to the input [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore by superposition (since our differential equation is linear), the sum of the terms on the right hand side is a series representation of the system response.  **Input**|  | **Response**   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\rightsquigarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]c_1 +\\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } {\\color{orange}{a_n}} y_n^{(c)}(t) + {\\color{blue}{b_n}} y_n^{(s)}(t)[/mathjaxinline]      ### Program for solving inhomogeneous DEs with periodic input    1. Find a Fourier series approximation to the input signal **_(What we will learn today.)_**    2. The system response is the sum of the response to each [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos nt[/mathjaxinline] input. **_(Explore in 2 lectures from now.)_**  **Question:** Is it really useful to have a particular solution that is expressed as an infinite sum?  **Answer:** It is useful when you can determine which terms in the sum are dominant.  But first things first: we must define the Fourier series, determine how to compute it.  * converges to [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] at values of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous, and     * converges to -1[/mathjaxinline] and right limit [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}(0^+)=1[/mathjaxinline] average to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 39, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab15", "text": "So far, we have only worked with periodic functions and signals. In the real world, signals may not be periodic.  **Example 15.1** The function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) = e^{-t^2}[/mathjaxinline] is a non periodic function that is important in probability and differential equations.  **Example 15.2** Sound signals are not truly periodic as the signal exists for finite time.  ![ ](/static/images/soundwave_matlab.svg)    **Figure 12** : A sound wave coming from a narration of text.  Below let's generalize the method of Fourier series to non-periodic signals. This is known as the Fourier transform.  Suppose you have a radio signal, sound wave, or other signal [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] with period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline]. Then we can write the signal in the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t) = \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } c_k e^{(ik\\pi /L) t},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      where the [mathjaxinline]c_k[/mathjaxinline] are the coefficients determined by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_k = \\frac{1}{2L}\\int _{-L}^{L} f(t) e^{-(ik\\pi /L) t}\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      We can think of a non-periodic signal as the limit as [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] goes to infinity of a periodic signal of period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline]. As [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] increases, the spacing between the frequencies in our sum are approaching zero. This turns the sum into an integral in the limit, and we have the equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\widehat{f}\\left(k\\right)e^{ i k t} \\, dk[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widehat{f}(k)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2\\pi }\\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f\\left(t\\right)e^{- i k t} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We call [mathjaxinline]\\, \\widehat{f}\\left(k\\right) \\,[/mathjaxinline] the **Fourier transform** of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline].  Note that the continuous function [mathjaxinline]\\, \\widehat{f}(k) \\,[/mathjaxinline] replaces the discrete coefficients [mathjaxinline]\\, c_k \\,[/mathjaxinline]. So now [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\left(t\\right) \\,[/mathjaxinline] can be composed of a continuous infinite sum (an integral) of complex sinusoids [mathjaxinline]e^{i k t}[/mathjaxinline] with the weights being given by the [mathjaxinline]\\, \\widehat{f}(k) \\,[/mathjaxinline] function.  ###  A derivation of Fourier transform  The following argument does not constitute proof, but does show you how the formula for the Fourier transform arises. We leave out some technical conditions related to the convergence of the finite Fourier series and improper integral of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] (the function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x) \\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the Dirichlet conditions on every finite interval and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\left| f(x) \\right| \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] is finite).  Start with  [mathjax]f(t) = \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } c_k e^{i\\frac{k\\pi }{L} t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and make a change of variable so that [mathjaxinline]\\omega _k = k\\pi /L[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\omega _{k+1}-\\omega _k = \\pi /L = \\Delta \\omega[/mathjaxinline]. The Fourier series can be rewritten as the following, where the dummy variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] has been replaced by [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] in the equation for [mathjaxinline]c_k[/mathjaxinline] to avoid confusion.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } c_k e^{i\\omega _k t} ,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_k[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2L} \\int _{-L}^{L} f(t)e^{-i\\omega _k t} \\, dt \\, = \\, \\frac{1}{2L} \\int _{-L}^{L} f(u)e^{-i\\omega _k u} \\, du.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Substituting the expression for [mathjaxinline]c_k[/mathjaxinline] into the formula for [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] and using the fact that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2L} = \\frac{\\Delta \\omega }{2\\pi }[/mathjaxinline], we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\left[\\frac{\\Delta \\omega }{2\\pi } \\int _{-L}^{L} f(u)e^{-i\\omega _k u}\\, du \\right]e^{i\\omega _k t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\frac{\\Delta \\omega }{2\\pi } \\int _{-L}^{L} f(u)e^{-i\\omega _k u}e^{i\\omega _k t}\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Now take the limit as [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] tends to [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline]. We obtain  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{L\\rightarrow \\infty } \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\frac{\\Delta \\omega }{2\\pi } \\int _{-L}^{L} f(u)e^{-i\\omega _k u}e^{i\\omega _k t}\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\frac{d\\omega }{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(u)e^{-i\\omega u}e^{i\\omega t}\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(u)e^{-i\\omega u}e^{i\\omega t}\\, du\\, d\\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\left( \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(u)e^{-i\\omega u}\\, du \\right) e^{i\\omega t}\\, d\\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Define  [mathjax]\\widehat{f}(\\omega ) =\\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(u)e^{-i\\omega u}\\, du =\\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(t)e^{-i\\omega t}\\, dt ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then it follows that  [mathjax]f(t) = \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\widehat{f}(\\omega )e^{i\\omega t}\\, d\\omega .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In practice, the above Fourier transform is often a starting point for analysis of signals. However, discrete Fourier series are sufficient approximations in many cases. You'll likely encounter a Fourier transform in other courses. See for example 18.103, 18.303, 18.311, 18.353, and 18.354.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Generalizing Fourier series: The Fourier transform", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Generalizing Fourier series: The Fourier transform"}

{"pageid": 40, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab3", "text": "The wave equation is  [mathjax]\\underbrace{\\mu \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2}}_{\\text{mass times acceleration / unit length }} = \\underbrace{T \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}}_{\\text{force / unit length} }, \\qquad \\mu , T > 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the left hand side describes the mass times acceleration per unit length, and the right hand side is the force per unit length on the string.  Let's think about what this is telling us physically.  **Case 1:**   Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}>0[/mathjaxinline], that is a small segment of string is concave up.  ![Concave up segment with positive tension forces at ends and upwards acceleration](/static/images/u6s6_concaveup.svg)  The equation says that the net force is positive, hence the net acceleration is upwards.  This agrees with our expectations that if you imagine pulling on a concave up string along the tension forces, the string will accelerate upwards toward a straight configuration.  **Case 2:**   Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}<0[/mathjaxinline], that is a small segment of string is concave down.  ![Concave down segment with positive tension forces at ends and downwards acceleration](/static/images/u6s6_concavedown.svg)  The equation says that the net force is negative, hence the net acceleration is downwards.  This agrees with our expectations that if you imagine pulling on a concave down string along the tension forces, the string will accelerate downwards toward a straight configuration.  **Case 3:**   Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}=0[/mathjaxinline], that is a small segment of string is straight.  ![Straight segment with positive tension forces at ends and no acceleration](/static/images/u6s6_straight.svg)  The equation says that the net force is zero, hence the net acceleration is zero.  This agrees with our expectations that if you imagine pulling on a straight segment string along the tension forces, the string will not accelerate at all, and will remain straight.  Understanding", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Understanding"}

[mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\theta _{j}^{i+1}-\\theta _{j}^{i}}{\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\nu \\frac{\\theta _{j+1}^{i}-2\\theta _{j}^{i}+\\theta _{j-1}^{i}}{\\Delta x^{2}}+\\text{higher order terms}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta _{j}^{i+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta _{j}^{i}+\\frac{\\nu \\Delta t}{(\\Delta x)^2}\\left(\\theta _{j+1}^{i}-2\\theta {"pageid": 44, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab3", "text": "**Problem 3.1** Suppose that [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is an odd periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. Find the periodic function [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] that is a solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 50 x = f(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Think of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] as the input signal, and the solution [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] as the system response (output signal).  **Special case:** What is the system response to the input signal [mathjaxinline]\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline]? In other words, what is a solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 50 x = \\sin (nt)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with the same (smallest) period as [mathjaxinline]\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** First find the response to [mathjaxinline]e^{int}[/mathjaxinline], and then take the imaginary part. In other words, we first solve  [mathjax]\\ddot{z} + 50 z = e^{int}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r)=r^2+50[/mathjaxinline], so by ERF, the system response to [mathjaxinline]e^{int}[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]z = \\frac{1}{P(in)} e^{int} = \\frac{1}{50-n^2} e^{int}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The complex gain is [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{50-n^2}[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]x = \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left( \\frac{1}{50-n^2} e^{int} \\right) = \\frac{1}{50-n^2} \\sin (nt)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is the system response to [mathjaxinline]\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline]. This explains all the rows of the table below except the last row.  **Input Signal**|  **System Response**   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]e^{int}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{50-n^2} e^{int}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{50-n^2} \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{49} \\sin t[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\sin 2t[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{46} \\sin 2t[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\sin 3t[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{41} \\sin 3t[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\vdots[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\vdots[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1} \\frac{1}{50-n^2} b_n \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline]  Solving ODEs", "filename": "solveodes-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Solving ODEs"}

{"pageid": 45, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab14", "text": "### The coefficients of the complex Fourier series  The coefficients of the complex Fourier series, [mathjaxinline]c_n[/mathjaxinline], are complex numbers. To visualize them, we typically look at the magnitudes [mathjaxinline]|c_n|[/mathjaxinline], which are real. For example, suppose we have a real, [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic signal, such as the square wave.  ![ ](/static/images/SQwv_matlab.svg)    **Figure 8** : The Square wave with period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].      Then we can visualize the coefficients [mathjaxinline]|c_n|[/mathjaxinline] graphically as follows.  ![Plot of the magnitudes of the complex Fourier coefficients](/static/images/SQwv_fft.svg)    **Figure 9** : The frequencies [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n/2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] are displayed along the horizontal axis.   Magnitudes of the coefficients [mathjaxinline]|c_n|[/mathjaxinline] are plotted on the vertical axis.      The horizontal axis represents the frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n/2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], and the height of each bar represents the magnitude of each coefficient [mathjaxinline]c_n[/mathjaxinline]. Because the signal is real, [mathjaxinline]|c_n| = |c_{-n}|[/mathjaxinline], hence the graph is symmetric about [mathjaxinline]n=0[/mathjaxinline].  To understand what this graph is telling us, remember that a sinusoid of frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] can be written in three equivalent ways.  Recall that  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(c e^{i\\theta }) =\\mathrm{Re\\, }(\\overline{c} e^{-i\\theta }) = A \\cos (\\theta - \\phi ), \\qquad |c| = A, \\mathrm{Arg}(c) = -\\phi .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (This was discussed in the lecture on sinusoids in course 1 _Introduction to Differential Equations_.)  Therefore  [mathjax]c e^{i\\theta } + \\overline{c}e^{-i\\theta } = 2A\\cos (\\theta -\\phi ),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n=-\\infty }^{\\infty }c_n e^{i\\omega _n t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_0 + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty }\\left(c_n e^{i\\omega _n t} + \\overline{c_n} e^{-i\\omega _n t}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_0 + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } 2A_n \\cos (\\omega _n t - \\phi _n).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore by knowing the magnitudes of the coefficients [mathjaxinline]|c_n|[/mathjaxinline], we know the amplitudes of the terms [mathjaxinline]A_n[/mathjaxinline], but we lose the information about the phase shifts [mathjaxinline]\\phi _n[/mathjaxinline].  When we are interested in real signals that are coming from the sound of a single note, losing the information about the phase shift is OK. The reason being that we cannot actually discern phase shifts in sound signals. So this loss of information is not detrimental to our understanding of the signal.  Verify to yourself that you cannot hear phase shifts using the mathlet below.    1. Create a real signal. Set values of [mathjaxinline]|c_n|[/mathjaxinline], and make sure that [mathjaxinline]|c_{-n}| = |c_n|[/mathjaxinline] by clicking the box \"f(t) real\" in the upper left corner.     2. By default all of the phase shifts are zero. You can change the phase shifts for each [mathjaxinline]c_n[/mathjaxinline] using the sliders in the bottom screen.     3. **Warning:** Pure sinusoids can be damaging to your hearing. We recommend keeping the volume level low, and do not listen for too long! (Also, we recommend using lower frequencies, and keeping the amplitudes of higher frequencies small.)     4. Press play. Manipulate the phase shifts and see if you can hear any difference in the sound signal!     5. Press pause! Please don't damage your hearing.   Coefficients", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab14-text2.html", "title": "Coefficients"}

{"pageid": 46, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab4", "text": "**Problem 4.1** How many solutions are there to the initial value problem  [mathjax]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}v(x) = \\lambda v(x), \\qquad v(0) = 3, \\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dv}{dx}(0) = 5,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is a parameter that can take on any real number value?  ###  Answer  There is 1 solution, by the existence and uniqueness theorem.  **Recall the existence and uniqueness theorem for linear ODEs.** Let [mathjaxinline]p_{n-1}(t),\\dotsc , \\, p_0(t), q(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be continuous functions on an open interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] be in the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, I,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and let [mathjaxinline]b_0,\\dotsc ,b_{n-1}\\,[/mathjaxinline] be given numbers. Then there exists a unique solution to the [mathjaxinline]n^{\\text{th}}[/mathjaxinline] order linear ODE  [mathjax]y^{(n)}+p_{n-1}(t)y^{(n-1)}+\\cdots +p_1(t)\\dot{y}+p_0(t) y=q(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      satisfying the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] initial conditions  [mathjax]y(a)=b_0,\\quad \\dot{y}(a)=b_1,\\quad \\dotsc ,\\quad y^{(n-1)}(a)=b_{n-1}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Existence** means that there is at least one solution; **uniqueness** means that there is only one solution.    [Show](javascript: {return false;})  This is an initial value problem since the conditions are the value and first derivative **at the same point.** In contrast, a **boundary value problem** has conditions at different points.  Consider the following family of examples, one for each [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline]:  **Problem 4.2** Find all functions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline][0,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline] satisfying [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}v(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x)[/mathjaxinline] for a constant [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] and satisfying the **boundary conditions** [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline].  Even though there are the right number of conditions, there is no longer any guarantee that they specify a unique solution \u2014 there is no existence and uniqueness theorem for boundary value problems. For most values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline], it will turn out that this problem has a unique solution (namely, [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]), but for special values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline], we will see that it has infinitely many solutions!    * The example in problem 4.2 is called a **homogeneous linear boundary value problem,** and can have one solution or infinitely many solutions.     * An **inhomogeneous linear boundary value problem** could have zero solutions, one solution, or infinitely many solutions.     * The situation for **nonlinear boundary value problems** is even more complicated.   Our goal is to use boundary conditions for PDEs, but ODEs can have boundary conditions as well. In general, ODEs are much easier to solve than PDEs, so we now move our discussion to ODEs with boundary conditions to get a sense of how to solve these **boundary value problems** in a more comfortable setting.  Failure of existence and uniqueness", "filename": "bvp-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Failure of existence and uniqueness"}

{"pageid": 47, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab5", "text": "**Summary:**    * We modeled an insulated metal rod with exposed ends held at [mathjaxinline]0^\\circ \\text{C}[/mathjaxinline].     * Using physics, we found that its temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] was governed by the PDE   [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}, \\quad 0 < x < \\pi , \\quad \\text{(the heat equation).}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      For simplicity, we specialized to the case [mathjaxinline]\\nu =1[/mathjaxinline], length [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline], and initial temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0) = 1[/mathjaxinline].    * Trying [mathjaxinline]\\theta = v(x)\\, w(t)[/mathjaxinline] led to separate ODEs for [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline], leading to solutions [mathjaxinline]e^{-n^2 t} \\sin nx[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]n=1,2,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline] to the PDE with boundary conditions.     * We took linear combinations to get the general solution   [mathjax]\\boxed {\\theta (x,t) = b_1 e^{-t} \\sin x + b_2 e^{-4t} \\sin 2x + b_3 e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\cdots }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      to the PDE with homogeneous boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta (0,t) = 0[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\theta (\\pi , t) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Initial conditions.** As usual, we postponed imposing the initial condition, but now it is time to impose it.  **Question 5.1** Which choices of [mathjaxinline]b_1,b_2,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline] make the general solution above also satisfy the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0) = 1[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x \\in (0,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline]?  Set [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] in  [mathjax]\\text{General solution:}\\quad \\theta (x,t) = b_1 e^{-t} \\sin x + b_2 e^{-4t} \\sin 2x + b_3 e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\cdots[/mathjax]| (4.7)   ---|---      (the general solution to the Heat Equation) and use the initial condition on the left to get  [mathjax]1 = b_1 \\sin x + b_2 \\sin 2x + b_3 \\sin 3x + \\cdots \\quad \\text{for }\\space x \\in (0,\\pi ),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which must be solved for [mathjaxinline]b_1,b_2,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline].  Because the right hand side is odd and of base period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], to find such [mathjaxinline]b_i[/mathjaxinline], the left hand side must be extended to an odd period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] function, namely [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}(x)[/mathjaxinline]. So we need to solve  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(x) = b_1 \\sin x + b_2 \\sin 2x + b_3 \\sin 3x + \\cdots \\quad \\text{for all } x \\in \\mathbb {R}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We already know the answer:  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(x) = \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\sin x + \\frac{4}{3\\pi } \\sin 3x + \\frac{4}{5\\pi } \\sin 5x + \\cdots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words [mathjaxinline]b_n=0[/mathjaxinline] for even [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]b_n = \\frac{4}{n\\pi }[/mathjaxinline] for odd [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]. Substituting these [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] back into the general solution to the heat equation gives  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi } e^{-t} \\sin x + \\frac{4}{3\\pi } e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\frac{4}{5\\pi } e^{-25t} \\sin 5x + \\cdots . \\quad[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Question 5.2** What does the temperature profile look like when [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is large?  **Answer:** All the Fourier components are decaying, so [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t) \\to 0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline] at every position. Thus the temperature profile approaches a horizontal segment, the graph of the zero function. But the Fourier components of higher frequency decay much faster than the first Fourier component, so when [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is large, the formula  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) \\approx \\frac{4}{\\pi } e^{-t} \\sin x[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is a very good approximation. Eventually, the temperature profile is indistinguishable from a sinusoid of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] whose amplitude is decaying to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. This can be observed in the mathlet.  Initial conditions", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Initial conditions"}

{"pageid": 49, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab9", "text": "**Remark 9.1** We have talked about waves moving in one space dimension, but waves exist in higher dimensions too.    * In one dimension, a disturbance created wave fronts moving to the left and right, and the space-time diagram of the wave front was shaped like a V.     * In two dimensions, the disturbance caused by a pebble dropped in a still pond creates a circular wave front that moves outward in all directions. The space-time diagram of this wave front is shaped like an ice cream cone (without the ice cream).     * In three dimensions, the wave front created by a disturbance at a point is an expanding sphere. {"pageid": 50, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**  After this section and some practice, you should be able to:    * Apply **superposition** and **separation of variables** to find a general solution to the 1-dimensional heat equation with **homogeneous boundary conditions.**    * Set [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] in the general solution to obtain a **Fourier series** solution describing the **initial condition.** Apply the initial condition to determine the **Fourier coefficients** of that series.     * Find a **particular solution** to the 1-dimensional heat equation with **inhomogeneous boundary conditions.**    * Recognize the **diffusion equation** as analogous to the heat equation, and solve using Fourier methods with different boundary conditions.
