{"pageid": 51, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab10", "text": "**Example 10.2**  (Try working this problem out on your own before looking at the solution, and compare to the previous problem solution.)  Consider an infinitely long string that is free at one end and modeled this by the wave equation on the half-line [mathjaxinline]x > 0[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad x > 0, \\, \\, t> 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the end of the string is free at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline].  The boundary condition at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}(0,t) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Suppose the initial conditions are  [mathjax]u(x,0)=s(x-1) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)= 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      a step function pulse centered at [mathjaxinline]x=1[/mathjaxinline] with zero initial velocity.  ![Step function centered at x=1 defined only for x>0](/static/images/u6_initial_xpos.svg)    **Figure 28** :  Initial position defined for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline]      If we let [mathjaxinline]f(x) = s(x-1)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline], then the **incoming wave** (left traveling wave) [mathjaxinline]f(x+ct)[/mathjaxinline] obeys the PDE and the initial condition ([mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline]), but does not obey the boundary condition ([mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline]).  Determine the proper **reflected wave** (right traveling wave) [mathjaxinline]g(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline] that needs to be added to the incoming wave in order to satisfy the Neumann boundary condition.  Draw the corresponding wavefronts in the [mathjaxinline](x,t)[/mathjaxinline] plane.  ###  See worked solution  Let [mathjaxinline]u(x,t) = f(x+ct) + g(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]\\frac{du}{dx}(x,t) = f'(x+ct) + g'(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline]. At [mathjaxinline]x = 0[/mathjaxinline], we get [mathjaxinline]0 = f'(ct) + g'(-ct)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus [mathjaxinline]g'(x) = - f'(-x)[/mathjaxinline], which can be integrated to get [mathjaxinline]g(x) = f(-x)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus [mathjaxinline]g(x) = s(-x-1)[/mathjaxinline]. In order to combine [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] to a function defined for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], we must extend the functions to both be defined for all real numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. The easiest way to do this is to define [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to be [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x<0[/mathjaxinline], and define [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] to be [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline]. We can do this by the formulas  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)s(-x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(x)s(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      By summing these two functions, we get an initial condition to be an even function defined everywhere [mathjaxinline]U(x,0) = s(x-1)s(-x) + s(-x-1)s(x)[/mathjaxinline].  ![Step function centered at x=1 for x positive extended to an even function on all real numbers](/static/images/u6_initial_allx_free.svg)    **Figure 29** : Even extension of initial condition defined for all [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline]      This tells us that the reflected wave bounced back at the free end with the same direction.  The space-time diagram includes    * a first line with slope [mathjaxinline]-1/c[/mathjaxinline] passing through [mathjaxinline](1,0)[/mathjaxinline] (the incident wave)     * a second line with slope [mathjaxinline]1/c[/mathjaxinline] passing through [mathjaxinline](-1,0)[/mathjaxinline] (the reflected wave)   ![Space-time diagram of wave front on half interval showing line of slope -1/c starting at x=1 hitting axis and being reflected by opposite sign wave front with slope 1/c](/static/images/wavefront_3.svg)  The two lines meet at [mathjaxinline](0,1/c)[/mathjaxinline], where the 2 waves superpose and add to briefly have amplitude [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]. The physical wave first travels as a left- going step function along the first line toward the origin, reflects because of the boundary condition, and then re-emerges as a right-going step function with amplitude [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  To help understand the process, the image below shows a series of photographs of the wave in the string for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline] with the extended even wave shown as a dotted line for a sequence of times starting from the initial position.  ![Series of snap shots of the wave propogating through the string x>0](/static/images/u6_initial_allx_free_step.svg)    [Show](javascript: {return false;})  New boundary condition", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab10-text2.html", "title": "New boundary condition"}

{"pageid": 56, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab3", "text": "### Review  We can think of the Fourier Series as a method that takes \u201cany\" periodic function, and replaces it with a discrete set of coefficients (infinitely many, but countably infinite).  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t) = f(t+2L)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{k=-\\infty }^{\\infty } c_k e^{ik\\pi t/L},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_k[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2L} \\int _{-L}^L f(t) e^{-ik\\pi t/L} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The Fourier Transform takes \u201cany\" function, and replaces it with a continuous function.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\widehat{f}(k) e^{ikt}\\, dk,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widehat{f}(k)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } f(t) e^{-ik t} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Review", "filename": "DFTLab-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Review"}

{"pageid": 57, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation6_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation6_for_edx-tab3", "text": "### Condition for numerical stability  [mathjax]\\boxed {\\frac{c\\Delta t}{\\Delta x}\\le 1.}[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Condition for numerical stability ", "filename": "recitation6_for_edx-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Condition for numerical stability "}

{"pageid": 58, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab2", "text": "In this section we meet our first partial differential equation (PDE)  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is the equation satisfied by the temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] at position [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] of a bar depicted as a segment,  [mathjax]0 \\le x \\le L, \\quad t \\ge 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![Horizontal line segment of length L](/static/images/heateqn_img1.svg)  The constant [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline] is the heat diffusion coefficient, which depends on the material of the bar.  We will focus on one physical experiment. Suppose that the initial temperature is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], and then the ends of the bar are put in ice. We write this as  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\theta (x,0) = 1, \\quad 0 \\le x \\le L}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---   [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{ \\theta (0,t) = 0, \\quad \\theta (L,t) = 0, \\quad t >0}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The value(s) of [mathjaxinline]\\theta =1[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] are called **initial conditions** . The values at the ends are called **endpoint or boundary conditions** . We think of the initial and endpoint values of [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] as the input, and the temperature [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]t>0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]0 < x < L[/mathjaxinline] as the response.  **Remark 2.1**  ###  Click to show remark  For simplicity, we assume that only the ends are exposed to the lower temperature. The rest of the bar is insulated, not subject to any external change in temperature. Fourier's techniques also yield answers even when there is heat input over time at other points along the bar.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  As time passes, the temperature decreases as cooling from the ends spreads toward the middle. At the midpoint, [mathjaxinline]L/2[/mathjaxinline], one finds Newton's law of cooling,  [mathjax]\\theta (L/2,t)\\approx c e^{-t/\\tau }, \\quad t >\\tau .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The so-called [characteristic time](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_constant#Thermal_time_constant) [mathjaxinline]\\tau[/mathjaxinline] is inversely proportional to the conductivity of the material and is proportional to the material thermal capacitance. If we choose units so that [mathjaxinline]\\tau =1[/mathjaxinline] for copper, then according to Wikipedia,  [mathjax]\\tau \\sim 7 \\quad \\text{(cast iron)}; \\quad \\tau \\sim 7000 \\quad \\text{(dry snow)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The constant [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], on the other hand, is **universal** :  [mathjax]c = \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\approx 1.3.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      It depends only on the fact that the shape is a bar (modeled as a line segment).  Fourier figured out not only how to explain [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] using differential equations, but the whole  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{\\text{temperature profile:}}} \\quad \\theta (x,t) \\approx e^{-t/\\tau } h(x);\\quad h(x) = \\frac4{\\pi } \\sin \\left(\\frac{\\pi }L x\\right),\\quad t > \\tau .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The shape of [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] shows that the temperature drop is less in the middle than at the ends. It's natural that [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] should be some kind of hump, symmetric around [mathjaxinline]L/2[/mathjaxinline].  **Heat Equation mathlet**  See the heat profile emerge as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases. It's remarkable that a sine function emerges out of the input [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)=1[/mathjaxinline]. There is no evident mechanism creating a sine function, no spring, no circle, no periodic input. The sine function and the number [mathjaxinline]4/\\pi[/mathjaxinline] arise naturally out of differential equations alone.  Introduction to the Heat Equation", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Introduction to the Heat Equation"}

{"pageid": 59, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab14", "text": "**Even functions:** If [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is an even, [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] periodic function, its Fourier series is  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } a_n \\cos (nt),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where (since [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\cos (nt)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an even function as well)  [mathjax]a_n = \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\int _{0}^{\\pi }f(t)\\cos (nt)\\, dt, \\qquad b_n=0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Odd functions:**  If [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is an odd, [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] periodic function, its Fourier series is  [mathjax]f(t) = \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } b_n \\sin (nt),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where (since [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\sin (nt)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an even function)  [mathjax]b_n = \\frac{2}{\\pi }\\int _{0}^{\\pi }f(t)\\sin (nt)\\, dt, \\qquad a_n=0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Summary of simplified formulas", "filename": "introtofourier-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Summary of simplified formulas"}

{"pageid": 60, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab10", "text": "For an additional reference, you might try the notes here: [Notes on beam theory from TUDelft](https://icozct.tudelft.nl/TUD_CT/CM5/collegestof/files/notes.pdf)  Reference", "filename": "bvp-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Reference"}

{"pageid": 61, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab7", "text": "Boundary conditions are most common when the independent variable is space rather than time. In time, we can typically only assign initial conditions. In space, it makes sense to specify conditions on the end points of a spatial object.  Let's consider some examples that arise from Linear Elasticity.  **Linear Elasticity for Vertical Beams**  Suppose we have a bar hanging vertically with the top end attached to a solid surface. The [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] coordinate is the spatial variable running along the length of the bar, so that each point on the non- elongated bar exists on the interval [mathjaxinline]y \\in [0, 1][/mathjaxinline].  ![Vertical beam fixed at the top and free at the bottom deformed by gravity.](/static/images/beam-1.svg)  Under its own weight, or an external force [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] pulling downwards, the bar will tend to lengthen. Thus each point on the bar will move to a new location, displaced by some amount [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline]. So that the new position of a point [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]y+u[/mathjaxinline].  The displacement [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is a function of **position,** [mathjaxinline]u=u(y)[/mathjaxinline].  Note the following analog of the situation described here, a simple experiment that you can conduct yourself. Take a slinky, and hang it on one end from the ceiling (or the under-side of a shelf).  ![](/static/images/slinkyfree2.png)    **Figure 18** : Slinky hanging from a fixed position at top.      Then the rings separate, with the separation between rings decreasing as you go down from the top. The [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] in our equation is then the distance from where a particular ring is at, to the position it would have if the slinky rings were placed right next to each other as if it were floating in zero gravity.  ![](/static/images/slinkycompressed2.png)    **Figure 19** : Slinky with rings placed next to each other in zero gravity.      Then the differential equation describing the displacement in terms of the external stress per coil (of slinky) [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2u}{dy^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{E}f(y),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.10)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where the constant [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline] is determined by the material elasticity.  When the external force is gravity, this equation becomes  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2u}{dy^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\frac{-\\rho g}{E},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.11)   ---|---|---|---|---      where the constant [mathjaxinline]\\rho[/mathjaxinline] is the density of the beam, and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is the constant of gravitational acceleration.  **Physics of Linear Elasticity**  ###  Click for derivation of differential equation  Note that the following is an abridged explanation of linear elasticity. Please note that the definition of [mathjaxinline]N(y)[/mathjaxinline] in what follows is slightly different than the function [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] above.    * above, [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] to denotes the external force per volume, in our case [mathjaxinline]f(y) = \\rho g[/mathjaxinline].     * below, [mathjaxinline]N(y)[/mathjaxinline] is the internal resultant of these external forces, which is defined as [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle N(y) = \\int _y^1 f(w) \\, dw[/mathjaxinline].   We have suppressed the derivation of this as this is not the focus of this class. To gain a deeper understanding, we recommend taking MITx course [2.01x Elements of Structures](https://www.edx.org/course/elements-of-structures).  There is a force per unit area on the bar, which arises from the deformation of the material and its elasticity. There is an internal resultant of this force, [mathjaxinline]N(y)[/mathjaxinline], which is felt by the cross- sectional area [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] through any position [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] on the vertical axis of the bar, is defined as **stress.**  Linear elasticity tells us that the stress is proportional to the strain. Let [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline] be this constant of proportionality. The **strain** is defined as the ratio of the relative change in length in any small (\"infinitesimal\") cross-section of the bar relative to its rest state.  In terms of the slinky, the strain is the ratio of the increment in separation between the coils under the stress, and their separation at rest.  To find the strain, choose two points in the non-elongated bar: [mathjaxinline]y_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y_2[/mathjaxinline]. In the elongated bar, the displacement of [mathjaxinline]y_1[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]u(y_1)[/mathjaxinline], and the displacement of [mathjaxinline]y_2[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]u(y_2)[/mathjaxinline]. So the total change in length between these two points is [mathjaxinline]u(y_2)-u(y_1)[/mathjaxinline]. The initial length of the bar between these two points is [mathjaxinline]y_2-y_1[/mathjaxinline].  ![The undeformed and deformed beam at two locations.](/static/images/beam-1b.svg)  The ratio is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u(y_2)-u(y_1)}{y_2-y_1}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\Delta u}{\\Delta y}[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.12)   ---|---|---|---|---      Taking the limit as [mathjaxinline]y_2[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]y_1[/mathjaxinline], we get the strain [mathjaxinline]\\left.\\frac{du}{dy}\\right|_{y=y_1}[/mathjaxinline].  Let [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline] be this constant of proportionality relating the stress [mathjaxinline]N(y)/A[/mathjaxinline] to the strain [mathjaxinline]\\frac{du}{dy}[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle EA\\frac{du}{dy}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle N(y).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.13)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Boundary Conditions**   **Case 1: Fix one end, other end hanging free**  ![A vertical beam fixed at the top, and deformed under gravity.](/static/images/beam-1.svg)     **Figure 20** : **Boundary conditions:** [mathjaxinline]u(0)=0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{du}{dy}(1)=0[/mathjaxinline]      Note that [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] represents the displacement of a point, and so points on the bar that are not displaced in the stretching will not move. Since the top of the bar is firmly set in place, this gives us our first boundary condition,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.14)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      At any cross-section along the beam, the force per unit area [the stress] has to be just enough to support the weight of the bar below this point. Thus:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle EA\\frac{du}{dy}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle gW(y)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.15)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]W(y)[/mathjaxinline] is the mass of the bar below [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. Suppose the density [mathjaxinline]\\rho[/mathjaxinline] of the beam and the cross sectional area [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] are both constant along the beam. Then  [mathjax]W(y) = \\int _y^1 \\rho A \\, dx = \\rho A (1-y);[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is the length of the beam.  Taking derivatives this becomes  [mathjax]AE\\frac{d^2u}{dy^2} = \\frac{d}{dy}gW(y) = -g\\rho A.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that at the end of our bar, there is no force per unit area, since there is no weight there. So we require the second boundary condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u'(1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.16)   ---|---|---|---|---       **Question 7.1** What is the formula for the displacement [mathjaxinline]u(y)[/mathjaxinline] if the force is gravity acting along a uniform beam?  ###  See worked solution  The differential equation can be written as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2 u}{d y^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-g\\rho }{E}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.17)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We can just integrate this twice, using the constants of integration [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] the first and second time, respectively, to find  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{-g\\rho }{E}y^2 + c_1 y + c_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.18)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      When we plug these boundary conditions into our differential equation, we get the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.19)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{du}{dy}(1)= 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-g\\rho }{E} + c_1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.20)      We can see immediately that [mathjaxinline]c_1 = \\frac{g\\rho }{E}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2 = 0[/mathjaxinline], which gives us the solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{g\\rho }{E}y^2 + \\frac{g\\rho }{E}y.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.21)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Beam Theory", "filename": "bvp-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Beam Theory"}

{"pageid": 64, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab6", "text": "Everything we did with periodic functions of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] can be generalized to periodic functions of other periods.  **Problem 6.1** Define  [mathjax]f(t) \\colon =\\begin{cases} 1 & \\text{ if } 0<t<1, \\\\\\ 0 & \\text{ if } -1<t<0\\. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![Plot of function defined above](/static/images/u6_step_periodic.svg)  and extend it to a periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]. Express this new square wave [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}[/mathjaxinline]. Then use the known Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}[/mathjaxinline] to find the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** This function is neither even nor odd. However, if we shift the function downwards by [mathjaxinline]1/2[/mathjaxinline], it is an odd function.  ![Shift of graph down vertically by half to make it an odd function](/static/images/u6_step_shiftdown.svg)      Write the shifted function  [mathjax]s(t) = f(t) -1/2 = \\begin{cases} 1/2 & 0 < t < 1\\\\\\ -1/2 & -1 < t < 0\\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If we multiply this function by [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]2s(t) = 2f(t) -1 = \\begin{cases} 1 & 0 < t < 1\\\\\\ -1 & -1 < t < 0\\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![Scale vertical axis by 2](/static/images/u6_step_scaleup.svg)      what we get is very similar to the square wave of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  ![Square wave of period 2pi](/static/images/u6_squarewave_orange.svg)      To avoid confusion, let's use [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] as the variable for [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Sq}[/mathjaxinline]. Scaling the horizontal axis by factor of [mathjaxinline]1/\\pi[/mathjaxinline] produces the graph of [mathjaxinline]2s(t)[/mathjaxinline].  ![Scaled horizontal axis](/static/images/u6_streched.svg)      In other words, if [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] are related by [mathjaxinline]u = \\pi t[/mathjaxinline] (so that [mathjaxinline]u=\\pi[/mathjaxinline] corresponds to [mathjaxinline]t=1[/mathjaxinline]), then [mathjaxinline]2s(t) = \\mathrm{Sq}(u)[/mathjaxinline]. In other words,  [mathjax]2s(t) = \\mathrm{Sq}\\left( \\pi t \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore,  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{1}{2} + s(t) = \\frac{1}{2}+ \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{Sq}(\\pi t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since we know the Fourier series  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(u) = \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}}\\frac{\\sin (nu)}{n},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac12 + \\frac2{\\pi }\\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin (n\\pi t)}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline] functions  Similarly we can scale the horizontal axis of any function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] to get a function of different period. Let [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] be a positive real number. Start with \u201cany\" periodic function  [mathjax]g(u) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} a_n \\cos nu + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin nu,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. Stretching horizontally by a factor [mathjaxinline]L/\\pi[/mathjaxinline] gives a periodic function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] of period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline], and \u201cevery\" [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] of period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline] arises this way. By the same calculation as above,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g\\left(\\frac{\\pi t}{L} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} a_n \\cos \\frac{n \\pi t}{L} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin \\frac{n \\pi t}{L}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The substitution [mathjaxinline]u = \\frac{\\pi t}{L}[/mathjaxinline] (and [mathjaxinline]du = \\frac{\\pi }{L} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline]) also leads to Fourier coefficient formulas for period [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi g(u) \\cos nu \\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-L}^L g \\left(\\frac{\\pi t}{L}\\right) \\cos \\left(\\frac{n \\pi t}{L}\\right) \\frac{\\pi }{L} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{L} \\int _{-L}^L f(t) \\cos \\left(\\frac{n \\pi t}{L}\\right) \\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      A similar formula gives [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline].  Functions of Arbitrary period", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Functions of Arbitrary period"}

{"pageid": 67, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@partB03/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@partB03-tab3", "text": "Baking a cake is actually a complicated process. Here, we vastly simplify the process by modeling the baking of a 1-dimensional cake of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] that starts at room temperature (20 [mathjaxinline]^{\\circ }\\text{C}[/mathjaxinline]). One end is exposed directly to the oven temperature (200 [mathjaxinline]^{\\circ }\\text{C}[/mathjaxinline]). The thin 1-D cake is insulated and the other end is insulated by the pan.  The main difference in this model is that we assume that both the thermal conductivity [mathjaxinline]k(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] and the heat capacity [mathjaxinline]c(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] vary with respect to temperature. We ignore all other baking effects.  In this case, the partial differential equation is  [mathjax]c(\\theta ) \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x}\\left(k(\\theta )\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial x}\\right) \\qquad 0 < x < L, \\, \\, t>0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The initial condition is  [mathjax]\\theta (x,0)=20, \\qquad 0 < x < L.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The boundary conditions are  [mathjax]\\theta (0,t)=200, \\quad \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x}\\theta (L,t)=0, \\qquad t>0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This partial differential equation cannot be solved by separation of variables. However, it can be solved numerically. In the following problems, we will guide you through developing a function to model the thermal conductivity [mathjaxinline]k(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] and heat capacity [mathjaxinline]c(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline], and then discretize and solve this PDE for cakes of different sizes to compare the baking time.  Setup", "filename": "partB03-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Setup"}

{"pageid": 68, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab12", "text": "**Flux boundary condition**  If we are prescribing the flow rate of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] at the boundary, this is just the flux times the cross section  [mathjax]\\displaystyle qA = -A\\alpha \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}.[/mathjax]| (4.23)   ---|---      For a pipe of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] with boundaries at [mathjaxinline]x=0,L[/mathjaxinline], after multiplying the constant factors all together, we get the conditions for [mathjaxinline]t > 0[/mathjaxinline] as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}(0,t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = a[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.24)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}(L,t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = b[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.25)      where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are constants. Note we could have [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] vary with time, but the techniques for solving such partial differential equations are beyond the level of this class. In general, boundary conditions that set the derivative at a boundary are known as **Neumann** boundary conditions.  Flux Boundary Condition", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Flux Boundary Condition"}

{"pageid": 70, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab8", "text": "In this section, we derive the fourth order differential equation that describes the static bending of a slender, horizontal beam due to a distributed load. The main simplifying assumption we are making is that we are only modeling the steady state, static bending. That is our model will not change in time, so there will be no time derivatives. The other simplifying assumption is that the beam does not bend very much.  We start the modeling process by drawing a picture, and labeling the relevant variables.  ![ ](/static/images/beamderiv_1.svg)    **Figure 23** : Undeformed beam      We will start with a beam that is pinned at both ends, which we draw by placing it on little triangles that are stuck into the ground. We label the vertical direction as the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis, and the horizontal direction along the undeformed beam is the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis. The quantity we wish to describe is the vertical displacement, or deflection, [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] of the beam at every point [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] along the beam.  ![ ](/static/images/beamderiv_2.svg)   Deformed beam      **Geometric quantities of interest**|  **Variable name**|   ---|---|---   Vertical deflection of the beam at each point | [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] |   Slope of the beam at each point |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dv}{dx}(x)[/mathjaxinline] |   Curvature of the beam at each point |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2}(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  (assuming that the deflection [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] is small)      Our goal is to determine [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] given    * the loading on the beam,     * the boundary conditions (constraints),     * the material of the beam, and     * the geometry of the beam.   Goal", "filename": "bvp-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Goal"}

{"pageid": 71, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab10", "text": "**Example 10.1** Consider an infinitely long string that is fixed at one end.  Model this by the wave equation on the half-line [mathjaxinline]x > 0[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad x > 0, \\, \\, t> 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the fixed end is at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline].  The boundary condition at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]u(0,t) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Suppose the initial conditions are  [mathjax]u(x,0)=s(x-1) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)= 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      a step function pulse centered at [mathjaxinline]x=1[/mathjaxinline] with zero initial velocity, defined for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline].  ![Step function centered at x=1 defined only for x>0](/static/images/u6_initial_xpos.svg)   _Initial position defined for [mathjaxinline]x >0[/mathjaxinline]_      If we let [mathjaxinline]f(x) = s(x-1)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline], then the **incoming wave** (left traveling wave) [mathjaxinline]f(x+ct)[/mathjaxinline] obeys the PDE and the initial condition ([mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline]), but does not obey the boundary condition ([mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline]).  Determine the proper **reflected wave** (right traveling wave) [mathjaxinline]g(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline] that needs to be added to the incoming wave in order to satisfy the Dirichlet boundary condition.  Draw the corresponding wavefronts in the [mathjaxinline](x,t)[/mathjaxinline] plane.  ###  Worked solution  Let [mathjaxinline]u(x,t) = f(x+ct) + g(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline]. At [mathjaxinline]x = 0[/mathjaxinline], the boundary condition gives [mathjaxinline]0 = f(ct) + g(-ct)[/mathjaxinline], hence we need to take [mathjaxinline]g(z) = - f(-z)[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore [mathjaxinline]g(x) = -s(-x-1)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x<0[/mathjaxinline].  Thus in order to solve this boundary value problem, we must extend the initial condition [mathjaxinline]U(x,0)[/mathjaxinline] to be defined for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. The first step is to extend [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] to functions [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] defined for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  Let [mathjaxinline]F(x) = s(x-1)s(-x)[/mathjaxinline]. This function is defined for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and is given by  [mathjax]F(x) = \\begin{cases} 0 & x < 0\\\\\\ 1 & 0 < x < 1 \\\\\\ 0 & x > 1 \\end{cases},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which is the behavior we want. Similarly, the [mathjaxinline]G(x) = -s(-x-1)s(x)[/mathjaxinline] has the correct properties so that  [mathjaxinline]U(x,0) = F(x) + G(x) = s(x-1)s(-x) - s(-x-1)s(x)[/mathjaxinline] is defined for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], and is an odd extension of [mathjaxinline]s(x-1)[/mathjaxinline] defined for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline].  ![Step function centered at x=1 for x positive extended to an odd function on all real numbers](/static/images/u6_initial_allx_fixed.svg)   _Odd extension of initial condition defined for all [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline]_      The space-time diagram includes    * a first line with slope [mathjaxinline]-1/c[/mathjaxinline] passing through [mathjaxinline](1,0)[/mathjaxinline] (the incident wave)     * a second line with slope [mathjaxinline]1/c[/mathjaxinline] passing through [mathjaxinline](-1,0)[/mathjaxinline] (the reflected wave)   ![Space-time diagram of wave front on half interval showing line of slope -1/c starting at x=1 hitting axis and being reflected by opposite sign wave front with slope 1/c](/static/images/wavefront_2.svg)  The two lines meet at [mathjaxinline](0,1/c)[/mathjaxinline], where the 2 waves cancel out exactly. The physical wave first travels as a left-going step function along the first line toward the origin, reflects because of the boundary condition, and then re-emerges as a right-going step function with amplitude [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline].  To help understand the process, the image below shows a series of photographs of the wave in the string for [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline] with the extended odd wave shown as a dotted line for a sequence of times starting from the initial position.  ![Series of snap shots of the wave propagating through the string x>0](/static/images/u6_initial_allx_fixed_step.svg)    [Show](javascript: {return false;})  In the next problem, we explore how to handle the case of a half-line [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline] with the end at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] free. To help you anticipate the mathematics, it may be helpful to watch the following demo video again and observe what is happening at the end points in the two boundary conditions shown: free and fixed.  This demo video was created by [TSG@MIT Physics](http://tsgphysics.mit.edu).  Applying boundary conditions", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Applying boundary conditions"}

{"pageid": 72, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab8", "text": "The solution that satisfies the initial condition is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\pi }{2} - \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\left( e^{-t} \\cos x + e^{-9t} \\frac{\\cos 3x}{9} + e^{-25 t} \\frac{\\cos 5x}{25} + \\dotsb \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This answer makes physical sense: when the entire bar is insulated, its temperature tends to a constant equal to the average of the initial temperature.  Continue solution", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab8-text2.html", "title": "Continue solution"}

{"pageid": 73, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab4", "text": "For simplicity, suppose that [mathjaxinline]c=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]L=\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. So now we are solving the PDE with boundary conditions  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad 0 < x < \\pi , \\, \\, t>0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(0,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(\\pi ,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      As with the heat equation, we try separation of variables. In other words, try to find normal modes of the form  [mathjax]u(x,t) = v(x) w(t),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some nonzero functions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Substituting this into the PDE gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v(x) \\ddot{w}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v^{\\prime \\prime }(x) w(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\ddot{w}(t)}{w(t)}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{v^{\\prime \\prime }(x)}{v(x)}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      As usual, a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] can equal a function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] only if both are equal to the same constant, say [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline], so this breaks into two ODEs:  [mathjax]\\ddot{w}(t) = \\lambda \\, w(t), \\qquad v^{\\prime \\prime }(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Moreover, the boundary conditions become [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline].  We already solved the eigenfunction equation [mathjaxinline]v^{\\prime \\prime }(x)=\\lambda \\, v(x)[/mathjaxinline] with the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline]: nonzero solutions exist only when [mathjaxinline]\\lambda = -n^2[/mathjaxinline] for some positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], and in this case [mathjaxinline]v = \\sin nx[/mathjaxinline] (times a scalar). What is different this time is that [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline] satisfies a **second** -order ODE  [mathjax]\\ddot{w}(t) = -n^2 \\, w(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]r^2+n^2[/mathjaxinline], which has roots [mathjaxinline]\\pm in[/mathjaxinline], so  [mathjax]w(t) = \\cos nt \\quad \\text{ and }\\quad w(t) = \\sin nt[/mathjax]|   ---|---      are possibilities (and all the others are linear combinations). Multiplying each by the [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] with the matching [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] gives the normal modes  [mathjax]\\cos (nt) \\sin (nx), \\qquad \\qquad \\sin (nt) \\sin (nx).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Any linear combination  [mathjax]\\displaystyle u(x,t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1} a_n \\cos (nt) \\sin (nx) + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} b_n \\sin (nt) \\sin (nx)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is a solution to the PDE with boundary conditions, and this turns out to be the general solution.  Normal modes", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab4-text2.html", "title": "Normal modes"}

{"pageid": 74, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab5", "text": "Let's continue exploring the family of homogeneous boundary value problems, one for each value of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] as in the previous page. But here we restrict our interest to the case where there are nonzero solutions.  **Problem 5.1** Find all **nonzero** functions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline][0,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline] satisfying [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}v(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x)[/mathjaxinline] for a constant [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] and satisfying the **boundary conditions** [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution to the problem:** The equation [mathjaxinline]v^{\\prime \\prime }(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x)[/mathjaxinline] is a homogeneous linear ODE with characteristic polynomial [mathjaxinline]r^2-\\lambda[/mathjaxinline].  **Case 1:** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda >0}}[/mathjaxinline] **.** Then the general solution is [mathjaxinline]a e^{\\sqrt{\\lambda } x} + b e^{-\\sqrt{\\lambda } x}[/mathjaxinline], and the boundary conditions say  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a + b[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.5)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a e^{\\sqrt{\\lambda } \\pi } + b e^{-\\sqrt{\\lambda } \\pi }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.6)      Since  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\\\ e^{\\sqrt{\\lambda } \\pi } & e^{-\\sqrt{\\lambda } \\pi } \\end{pmatrix} \\ne 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.7)   ---|---|---|---      the only solution to this linear system is [mathjaxinline](a,b)=(0,0)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus there are no nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline].  **Case 2:** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda =0}}[/mathjaxinline] **.** Then the general solution is [mathjaxinline]a + b x[/mathjaxinline], and the boundary conditions say  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.8)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a + b \\pi[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.9)      Again the only solution to this linear system is [mathjaxinline](a,b)=(0,0)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus there are no nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline].  **Case 3:** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda <0}}[/mathjaxinline] **.** We can write [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-\\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline] for some [mathjaxinline]\\omega >0[/mathjaxinline]. Then the roots of the characteristic polynomial are [mathjaxinline]\\pm i \\omega[/mathjaxinline], and the general solution is [mathjaxinline]a \\cos \\omega x + b \\sin \\omega x[/mathjaxinline]. The first boundary condition says [mathjaxinline]a = 0[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]v = b \\sin \\omega x[/mathjaxinline]. The second boundary condition then says [mathjaxinline]b \\sin \\omega \\pi = 0[/mathjaxinline]. We are looking for nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline], so we can assume that [mathjaxinline]b \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\omega \\pi = 0[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] is an integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]. It is enough to consider [mathjaxinline]n>0[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]\\sin (-\\omega x) =-\\sin (\\omega x)[/mathjaxinline].   **Conclusion:** There exist nonzero solutions if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-n^2[/mathjaxinline] for some positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]; in that case, all solutions are of the form [mathjaxinline]b \\sin nx[/mathjaxinline].  **We will use this conclusion as one step in the solution of the Heat Equation in the next lecture.**  Solving a boundary value problem", "filename": "bvp-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Solving a boundary value problem"}

{"pageid": 75, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@partB03/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@partB03-tab3", "text": "### Discretize the PDE  Let's numerically solve the heat equation  [mathjax]c(\\theta ) \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t}=\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x}k(\\theta )\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial x}, \\qquad 0 < x < L, \\, \\, t>0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta \\left(0,t\\right)=200[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x}\\theta \\left(L,t\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline] and initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta \\left(x,0\\right)=20[/mathjaxinline].  We will use a **forward in time, centered in space** numerical scheme. Let [mathjaxinline]\\theta _{j}^{i}[/mathjaxinline] denote the solution at time [mathjaxinline]i\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] and position [mathjaxinline]j\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline].  Then a discrete forward time time derivative is  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t}\\approx \\frac{\\theta _{j}^{i+1}-\\theta _{j}^{i}}{\\Delta t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To create the centered space derivative, we will take a backwards in space derivative the first time, and then a forwards in space derivative the second time.  What do we do about the values of [mathjaxinline]c(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]k(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline]?    * Evaluate [mathjaxinline]c(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] at the initial point in time.     * Take an average of the values of [mathjaxinline]k(\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] between the two points in space.   Substituting the discrete time and space derivatives into the heat equation above gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c(\\theta _{j}^{i})\\frac{\\theta _{j}^{i+1}-\\theta _{j}^{i}}{\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x} \\left(\\frac{k(\\theta _{j}^{i})+k(\\theta _{j-1}^{i})}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\theta _{j}^{i}-\\theta _{j-1}^{i}}{\\Delta x}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\left(\\frac{k(\\theta _{j+1}^{i})+k(\\theta _{j}^{i})}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\theta _{j+1}^{i}-\\theta _{j}^{i}}{\\Delta x}\\right) -\\left(\\frac{k(\\theta _{j}^{i})+k(\\theta _{j-1}^{i})}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\theta _{j}^{i}-\\theta _{j-1}^{i}}{\\Delta x}\\right) }{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta _{j}^{i+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta _{j}^{i}+ \\frac{\\Delta t}{2c(\\theta _{j}^{i})(\\Delta x)^2}\\left[ \\left(k(\\theta _{j+1}^{i})+k(\\theta _{j}^{i})\\right)\\left(\\theta _{j+1}^{i} - \\theta _{j}^{i}\\right)-\\left(k(\\theta _{j}^{i})+k(\\theta _{j-1}^{i})\\right)\\left(\\theta _{j}^{i}-\\theta _{j-1}^{i}\\right)\\right][/mathjaxinline] |  |      where at each time step [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] we impose the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta _{1}^{i}=200[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _{N}^{i}=\\theta _{N-1}^{i}[/mathjaxinline].  Discretize the PDE", "filename": "partB03-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Discretize the PDE"}

{"pageid": 77, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation6_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation6_for_edx-tab1", "text": "When we looked at waves propogating in a string, we were interested in how vertical displacements of the string changed over time. That is, all displacements were transverse, and we called these **transverse waves.** The equation modeling this motion is the wave equation  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The same wave equation models **longitudinal waves,** which occur when all of the motion occurs along the major axis. An example of a longitudinal wave is a **sound wave.** (For more about how sound waves works, you may want to check out the [following introductory videos](https://www.khanacademy.org/science/ap-physics-1/ap-mechanical-waves- and-sound/introduction-to-sound-waves-ap/v/sound-properties-amplitude-period- frequency-wavelength) from Khan Academy.)  In this recitation, we explore how the wave equation applies in the context of sound waves moving through a flute (modeled as a thin cylinder with open ends in air).  ![A thin cylinder with cross sectional area A, two open ends, contain moving air molecules.](/static/images/longitudinalwaves.svg)  Let us define the variables and assumptions.  **Variables and functions:** Define  [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] |  length of the cylinder   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] |  cross-sectional area of cylinder   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  position along the cylinder (from [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] | _horizontal_ displacement of the air molecules   [mathjaxinline]p_0[/mathjaxinline] |  ambient air pressure   [mathjaxinline]p(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] |  the difference in pressure away from the ambient air pressure      Here    * [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]p_0[/mathjaxinline] are constants;     * [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] are independent variables; and     * [mathjaxinline]u=u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]p = p(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] are functions defined for [mathjaxinline]x \\in [0,L][/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t \\ge 0[/mathjaxinline]. The horizontal displacement is measured relative to the equilibrium position in which (statistically) air molecules are evenly spaced and at ambient pressure.   **Assumptions:** All statistically significant air molecule motion occurs in the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-direction, and is small. Changes in pressure are small compared to the ambient air pressure.  Both the pressure and the horizontal displacement satisfy the wave equation  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^2 p}{\\partial t^2} = c^2\\frac{\\partial ^2 p}{\\partial x^2} \\qquad \\qquad \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad \\qquad 0 < x < L, \\quad t>0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is the speed of sound.  To understand boundary conditions, we need to understand how the pressure and horizontal displacement are related. The physics of sound involves three main ideas.    1. Moving air molecules cause changes in air density.     2. Changes in density correspond to changes in pressure.     3. Pressure differences generate motion of air molecules.   Let's look at what happens when we look at a small volume of air in our cylinder at equilibrium pressure [mathjaxinline]p_0[/mathjaxinline]. The volume [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] at equilibrium pressure is given by  [mathjax]V = A \\Delta x.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![Top is volume of air of width Delta x at equilibrium air pressure. Bottom is volume of air displaced by a pressure p.](/static/images/deltaV.svg)  If the pressure is changed from equilibrium to [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline], then the change in volume from equilibrium is  [mathjax]\\Delta V = A(u(x+\\Delta x) - u(x)) = A \\Delta u.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      All that is left is to understand how changes in pressure affect changes in volume. What we know is that if we increase the pressure on a given volume, the volume decreases. The decrease is proportional to the original volume [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] and the variation in pressure [mathjaxinline]p[/mathjaxinline]. This is captured in the equation  [mathjax]\\Delta V = -\\kappa V p,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\kappa[/mathjaxinline] is a physical constant.  Plugging in the expressions we found from the image for [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\Delta V[/mathjaxinline] involving [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\Delta u[/mathjaxinline] into our last equation, we find a relationship between pressure [mathjaxinline]p[/mathjaxinline] and displacement [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\Delta V[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\kappa V p[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A \\Delta u[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - \\kappa (A \\Delta x) p[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta u}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\kappa p.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\kappa p.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  How do instruments work", "filename": "recitation6_for_edx-tab1-text1.html", "title": "How do instruments work"}

{"pageid": 78, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab3", "text": "Recall that the exponential response formula gives us a quick method for finding the particular solution to any linear, constant coefficient, differential equations whose input can be expressed in terms of an exponential function.  **The exponential response formula (ERF):** Let [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a polynomial with real, constant coefficients, [mathjaxinline]\\, D = \\frac{d}{dt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] a differential operator, and [mathjaxinline]\\, r \\,[/mathjaxinline] a (real or complex) number. If [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) \\neq 0 \\,[/mathjaxinline], then a particular solution to the inhomogeneous differential equation  [mathjax]P(D)y = e^{rt} \\qquad \\text{is given by} \\qquad y_p = \\frac{e^{rt}}{P(r)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Caveat   ****Caveat: If [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) = P'(r) = P^{\\prime \\prime }(r) = \\dotsc =P^{(k-1)}(r)= 0\\,[/mathjaxinline], but [mathjaxinline]\\, P^{(k)}(r)\\neq 0 \\,[/mathjaxinline], then a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)y = e^{rt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjax]y_p = \\frac{t^ke^{rt}}{P^{(k)}(r)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ### Sinusoidal input:  [mathjaxinline]P(D)x = \\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] |  is the real part of |  [mathjaxinline]P(D)z = e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline];   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]P(D)x = \\sin (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] |  is the imaginary part of |  [mathjaxinline]P(D)z = e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline].      Therefore    * a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)x = \\cos (\\omega t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left[\\frac{e^{i\\omega t}}{P(i\\omega )} \\right]\\,[/mathjaxinline];     * a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)x = \\sin (\\omega t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle x_p = \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left[\\frac{e^{i\\omega t}}{P(i\\omega )} \\right]\\,[/mathjaxinline].   Review ERF", "filename": "introtofourier-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Review ERF"}

{"pageid": 80, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation6_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation6_for_edx-tab3", "text": "### Simple numerical method to solve the wave equation  We wish to numerically solve the wave equation  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial t^{2}}=c^{2}\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial x^{2}}[/mathjax]| (4.29)   ---|---      with the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]u\\left(0,t\\right)=f\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u\\left(L,t\\right)=g\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] and initial conditions [mathjaxinline]u\\left(x,0\\right)=q\\left(x\\right)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}\\left(x,0\\right)=s\\left(x\\right)[/mathjaxinline].  We will use a **centered time and space** numerical scheme. Let [mathjaxinline]u_{j}^{i}[/mathjaxinline] denote the solution at time [mathjaxinline]i\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] and position [mathjaxinline]j\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline]. Then the discrete (centered) second time derivative is  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial t^{2}}=\\frac{u_{j}^{i+1}-2u_{j}^{i}+u_{j}^{i-1}}{\\Delta t^{2}}+\\text{terms of order } \\left(\\Delta t^{2}\\right)\\text{ and higher} ,[/mathjax]| (4.30)   ---|---      and the discrete (centered) second space derivative is  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial x^{2}}=\\frac{u_{j+1}^{i}-2u_{j}^{i}+u_{j-1}^{i}}{\\Delta x^{2}}+\\text{terms of order }\\left(\\Delta x^{2}\\right)\\text{ and higher}.[/mathjax]| (4.31)   ---|---      Substituting the discrete time and space derivatives into the wave equation gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{j}^{i+1}-2u_{j}^{i}+u_{j}^{i-1}}{\\Delta t^{2}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c^{2}\\frac{u_{j+1}^{i}-2u_{j}^{i}+u_{j-1}^{i}}{\\Delta x^{2}}\\nonumber[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u_{j}^{i+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{c^{2}\\Delta t^{2}}{\\Delta x^{2}}\\left(u_{j+1}^{i}-2u_{j}^{i}+u_{j-1}^{i}\\right)+2u_{j}^{i}-u_{j}^{i-1}\\nonumber[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u_{j}^{i+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r^{2}u_{j+1}^{i}+2\\left(1-r^{2}\\right)u_{j}^{i}+r^{2}u_{j-1}^{i}-u_{j}^{i-1},\\quad r=\\frac{c\\Delta t}{\\Delta x} .\\nonumber[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In matrix notation, this is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} u_{1}^{i+1}\\\\\\ u_{2}^{i+1}\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ u_{N-1}^{i+1}\\\\\\ u_{N}^{i+1} \\end{pmatrix}=\\begin{pmatrix} 2\\left(1-r^{2}\\right) & r^{2}\\\\\\ r^{2} & 2\\left(1-r^{2}\\right) & r^{2}\\\\\\ & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\ddots \\\\\\ & & r^{2} & 2\\left(1-r^{2}\\right) & r^{2}\\\\\\ & & & r^{2} & 2\\left(1-r^{2}\\right) \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} u_{1}^{i}\\\\\\ u_{2}^{i}\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ u_{N-1}^{i}\\\\\\ u_{N}^{i} \\end{pmatrix}-\\begin{pmatrix} u_{1}^{i-1}\\\\\\ u_{2}^{i-1}\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ u_{N-1}^{i-1}\\\\\\ u_{N}^{i-1} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where at each time step [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] we impose the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]u_{1}^{i}=f\\left(i\\Delta t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u_{N}^{i}=g\\left(i\\Delta t\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. Note that to compute [mathjaxinline]u^{i+1}[/mathjaxinline], we need information about [mathjaxinline]u^{i}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u^{i-1}[/mathjaxinline]. So, how do we start the method (ensuring that our error has order less than [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t^{2}[/mathjaxinline])? We have that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u\\left(x,\\Delta t\\right)-u\\left(x,0\\right)}{\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}\\left(x,0\\right)+\\frac{\\Delta t}{2}\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial t^{2}}+\\mathcal{O}\\left(\\Delta t^{2}\\right)\\nonumber[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u\\left(x,\\Delta t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u\\left(x,0\\right)+\\Delta t\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}\\left(x,0\\right)+\\frac{c^{2}\\Delta t^{2}}{2}\\frac{\\partial ^{2}u}{\\partial x^{2}}\\left(x,0\\right)+\\mathcal{O}\\left(\\Delta t^{2}\\right).[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.32)      Discretizing gives  [mathjax]u_{j}^{1}=q_{j}+\\Delta t\\, s_{j}+\\frac{r^{2}}{2}\\left(q_{j+1}-2q_{j}+q_{j-1}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Numerically solving the wave equation", "filename": "recitation6_for_edx-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Numerically solving the wave equation"}

{"pageid": 82, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab4", "text": "Now let's return to the original problem. Suppose that the input signal [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is an odd periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is odd, the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is a linear combination of sine functions  [mathjax]f(t) = b_1 \\sin t + b_2 \\sin 2t + b_3 \\sin 3t + \\cdots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] be the input of the system  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 50 x = f(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      By the superposition principle, the system response to [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]x(t) = b_1 \\frac{1}{49} \\sin t + b_2 \\frac{1}{46} \\sin 2t + b_3 \\frac{1}{41} \\sin 3t + \\cdots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that each Fourier component [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] has a different gain: the gain depends on the frequency.  One could write a particular solution using sigma-notation:  [mathjax]\\boxed {x_p(t) = \\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1} \\frac{1}{50-n^2} b_n \\sin nt .}[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Fourier Series Input", "filename": "solveodes-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Fourier Series Input"}

{"pageid": 83, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation4_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation4_for_edx-tab3", "text": "Let's explore how to solve a differential equation with boundary conditions numerically.  We won't be able to use [mathjaxinline]\\texttt{ODE45}[/mathjaxinline], which requires _initial conditions_. Here we will detail how one can discretize the problem and reduce it to a problem in linear algebra instead!  Our example problem will be the vertical elastic beam, fixed at both ends, with force acting along its vertical axis.  ![A vertical beam fixed at the top and bottom.](/static/images/beam-2.svg)  This system satisfies the differential equation  [mathjax]\\frac{d^2u}{dy^2} = \\frac{f(y)}{E},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with boundary conditions  [mathjax]u(0)=0 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad u(1)=0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is the vertical displacement, [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] is the stress acting per unit length on the beam, and [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline] is the Young's Modulus (a constant determined by material properties of the beam).  The first step is to discretize the beam. The height [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is a continuous variable from 0 to 1. Create a series of evenly spaced points [mathjaxinline]y_1, \\dotsc y_N[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]y_1=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y_N=1[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]\\Delta y = y_{i+1}-y_i[/mathjaxinline].  ![Discretize the interval from 0 to 1.](/static/images/beam-2-discretize.svg)  Define [mathjaxinline]u_i = u(y_i)[/mathjaxinline].  What is the discrete version of [mathjaxinline]\\frac{du}{dy}[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]y_i[/mathjaxinline]? This is a subtle question because there isn't just one answer. The approach is to use a secant line approximation. The question is which points to use in the approximation. There are two equally good answers that seem the most natural.  Answer 1 |  Answer 2   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i+1}-u_i}{\\Delta y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i}-u_{i-1}}{\\Delta y}[/mathjaxinline]      Answer 1 might be called a forwards derivative; Answer 2, a backwards derivative.  What is the second derivative at [mathjaxinline]y_i[/mathjaxinline]? Now there are even more options.    * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i+2} - 2u_{i+1} + u_i}{(\\Delta y)^2}[/mathjaxinline] Forwards     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i+1} - 2u_{i} + u_{i-1}}{(\\Delta y)^2}[/mathjaxinline] Centered     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i} - 2u_{i-1} + u_{i-2}}{(\\Delta y)^2}[/mathjaxinline] Backwards   We will use the centered second derivative here. Let's see how to write out our differential equation as a system of linear equations.  For each [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline], we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{u_{i+1} - 2u_{i} + u_{i-1}}{(\\Delta y)^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(y_i)}{E}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u_{i+1} - 2u_{i} + u_{i-1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(y_i)\\Delta y^2}{E}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We can write this as a matrix equation  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} ? & ? & 0 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 & 1 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 1 & -2 & 1 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ & & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 1 & -2 & 1\\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 0 & ? & ? \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} u_1 \\\\\\ u_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ u_N \\end{pmatrix}= \\frac{(\\Delta y)^2}{E} \\begin{pmatrix} f(y_1) \\\\\\ f(y_2)\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ f(y_N) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The question of course is what to do at the end points.  The first thing to note is that we must enforce the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]u(0)=u_1=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u(1)=u_N = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the first equation in the matrix must be an equation setting this boundary condtion, and the last equation must set the other boundary condition. We can write this as follows:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 & 1 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 1 & -2 & 1 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ & & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 1 & -2 & 1\\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} u_1 \\\\\\ u_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ u_{N-1} \\\\\\ u_N \\end{pmatrix}= \\frac{(\\Delta y)^2}{E} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ f(y_2)\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ f(y_{N-1}) \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This matrix equation is just a system of linear equations and can be solved using MATLAB or other linear algebra techniques.  Toy example", "filename": "recitation4_for_edx-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Toy example"}

{"pageid": 85, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab6", "text": "Here we provide a table that outlines the analogy between linear algebra and Fourier techniques. {"pageid": 87, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab4", "text": "Let's now try to solve the PDE. For simplicity, suppose that [mathjaxinline]L=\\pi[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\theta _0=1[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\nu =1[/mathjaxinline]. _(The general case is similar. In fact, one could reduce to this special case by changes of variable.)_  So now we are solving  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad 0 < x < \\pi , \\, \\, t > 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta (0,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\quad \\text{for } t \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta (\\pi ,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\quad \\text{for } t \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta (x,0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1 \\quad \\text{for } x \\in (0,\\pi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Idea (separation of variables):** Forget about the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)=1[/mathjaxinline] for now, but look for nonzero solutions of the form  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) = v(x) \\, w(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (Note that we are making a slight change in notation.) Substituting into the PDE gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v(x)\\dot{w}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle w(t)v^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\dot{w}(t)}{w(t)}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{v''(x)}{v(x)}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (at least where [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w(t)[/mathjaxinline] are nonzero).  The only way for a function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] to equal to a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is if both functions are the same constant. That is, there is a constant [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]\\frac{v^{\\prime \\prime }(x)}{v(x)} = \\lambda \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\frac{\\dot{w}(t)}{w(t)} = \\lambda ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      or in other words,  [mathjax]v^{\\prime \\prime }(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\dot{w}(t) = \\lambda \\, w(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Substituting [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t) = v(x) w(t)[/mathjaxinline] into the first boundary condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (0,t)=0[/mathjaxinline] gives [mathjaxinline]v(0)w(t) = 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], but [mathjaxinline]w(t)[/mathjaxinline] is not the zero function, so this translates into [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline]. Similarly, the second boundary condition [mathjaxinline]\\theta (\\pi ,t)=0[/mathjaxinline] translates into [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline].  We already solved [mathjaxinline]v^{\\prime \\prime }(x) = \\lambda \\, v(x)[/mathjaxinline] subject to the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline]: nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] exist only if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-n^2[/mathjaxinline] for some positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], and in that case [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] is a scalar times [mathjaxinline]\\sin nx[/mathjaxinline].  For [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-n^2[/mathjaxinline], what is a matching possibility for [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline]? Since [mathjaxinline]\\dot{w} = -n^2 w[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline] is a scalar times [mathjaxinline]e^{-n^2 t}[/mathjaxinline].  This gives rise to one solution  [mathjax]\\theta _n(x,t) = e^{-n^2 t} \\sin nx[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for each positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], to the PDE with boundary conditions. Each such solution is called a **normal mode** .  Because the boundary conditions are homogeneous, we can get other solutions by taking linear combinations that also satisfy the homogeneous boundary conditions:  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) =b_1 e^{-t} \\sin x + b_2 e^{-4t} \\sin 2x + b_3 e^{-9t} \\sin 3x + \\cdots .[/mathjax]| (4.6)   ---|---      This turns out to be the general solution to the PDE [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\nu \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}[/mathjaxinline] with the boundary conditions [mathjaxinline]\\theta (0,t)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta (\\pi , t) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Separation of variables; Normal modes", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Separation of variables; Normal modes"}
