{"pageid": 89, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab3", "text": "### A new problem  Suppose we have a discrete set of [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] data points [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_{N-1}[/mathjaxinline] sampled over equal time increments [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline]. Define  [mathjax]t_n = \\underbrace{\\Delta t}_{\\text{fixed}} n.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![See caption](/static/images/u6_DFT_im1.svg)  **Figure 13** : [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] data points sampled over equal time intervals [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline]       **Goal:** Fit the data with a sum of sines and cosines (or really with complex exponentials using a complex Fourier series). That is, determine all of the \u201cfrequencies\" in this discrete set of data points.  **First step: Make it periodic.** Add another point [mathjaxinline]t_N[/mathjaxinline] and define [mathjaxinline]y_N = y_0[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.1** Let [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g(t)[/mathjaxinline] be two functions that fit all of the data [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_{N-1}[/mathjaxinline], and satisfying  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t_N)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t_0)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(t_N)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(t_0)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      ![See caption](/static/images/u6_DFT_im2.svg)  **Figure 14** : A function periodic function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] in solid black line goes through all data points.   Another periodic function [mathjaxinline]g(t)[/mathjaxinline] in dashed black goes through the same data.      We can extend [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g(t)[/mathjaxinline] to functions that are periodic of period [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t N[/mathjaxinline].  This implies that we can write  [mathjax]f(t) = \\sum _{k = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c_ke^{ik\\pi t/(t_N/2)} = \\sum _{k = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c_ke^{i2\\pi kt/N\\Delta t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some set of complex coefficients [mathjaxinline]c_k[/mathjaxinline].  And  [mathjax]g(t) = \\sum _{k = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c'_ke^{i2\\pi kt/N\\Delta t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for a set of coefficients [mathjaxinline]c'_k \\neq c_k[/mathjaxinline].  **The problem** Any way of filling in the space between the points leads to a new function, with a new set of coefficients. Thus there are infinitely many ways to fit the data with sines and cosines (or equivalently, with complex exponentials as we are actually doing here).  **Modified goal** Represent the data as simply as possible with a continuous function obtained as a sum of complex exponentials.  Observe that when we compare complex exponentials only at the the discrete times where we sampled our data,  [mathjax]e^{i2\\pi k {\\color{orange}{t_n}} / N\\Delta t} = e^{i2\\pi k ({\\color{orange}{n\\Delta t}} )/ N\\Delta t} = e^{i2\\pi kn/N}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      we cannot distinguish the difference between the [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline]th and the [mathjaxinline]k+N[/mathjaxinline]th frequency  [mathjax]e^{i2\\pi ({\\color{orange}{k+N}} ) t_n/ N\\Delta t} = e^{i2\\pi kn/N} \\underbrace{e^{ i2\\pi n}}_{1} = e^{i2\\pi kn/N}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus [mathjaxinline]e^{i2\\pi kt/N\\Delta t} = e^{i2\\pi (k+N)t/N\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline] whenever [mathjaxinline]t = t_n = n\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.2** Consider the set of data that are all equal to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  ![See caption](/static/images/u6_DFT_im3.svg)  **Figure 15** : Sampled data all equal to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. Both the constant function [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] (dashed line) and [mathjaxinline]\\cos (2\\pi t/\\Delta t)[/mathjaxinline] (solid line) pass through all data.   Represented as the real parts of complex exponentials, the dashed line is [mathjaxinline]e^{i0}[/mathjaxinline], and the solid line is [mathjaxinline]e^{i2\\pi t/\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline].      There are multiple frequencies that fit the data. Any frequencies higher than the sampling frequency cannot be detected in the data.  Because the [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline]th and the [mathjaxinline](k+N)[/mathjaxinline]th modes are equal when evaluated on the discrete times [mathjaxinline]t_k[/mathjaxinline], we can represent the data uniquely by the discrete time Fourier series  [mathjax]y(t) = \\sum _{k=0}^{N-1} c_k e^{\\frac{i2\\pi k t}{N\\Delta t}},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some complex coefficients [mathjaxinline]c_0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline], , [mathjaxinline]c_{N-1}[/mathjaxinline].  So, how do we actually compute these coefficients?  Define [mathjaxinline]\\omega = e^{i 2\\pi /N}[/mathjaxinline], which is the [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline]th root of unity, where we have [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] data points.  Let's look at how our data points are represented in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(0) = c_0 + c_1 + c_2 + \\dotsb + c_{N-1}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(\\Delta t) = c_0 + c_1\\omega ^1 + c_2\\omega ^2 + \\dotsb + c_{N-1}\\omega ^{N-1}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(2\\Delta t) = c_0 + c_1\\omega ^2 + c_2\\omega ^4 + \\dotsb + c_{N-1}\\omega ^{2(N-1)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\vdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{N-1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_0 + c_1\\omega ^{N-1} + c_2\\omega ^{2(N-1)} + \\dotsb + c_{N-1}\\omega ^{(N-1)(N-1)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore we can write this data as a matrix equation  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} y_0 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ y_{N-1} \\end{pmatrix}= \\mathbf{W}_N \\begin{pmatrix} c_0 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ c_{N-1} \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where  [mathjax]\\mathbf{W}_N = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 & \\cdots & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & \\omega & \\omega ^2 & \\cdots & \\omega ^{N-1} \\\\\\ 1 & \\omega ^2 & \\omega ^4 & \\cdots & \\omega ^{2(N-1)} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & & \\vdots \\\\\\ 1 & \\omega ^{N-1} & \\omega ^{2(N-1)} & \\cdots & \\omega ^{(N-1)(N-1)} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that we can describe this as the coefficient in the [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline]th row and [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th column is [mathjaxinline](\\mathbf{W}_N)_{ij} = \\omega ^{(i-1)(j-1)}[/mathjaxinline].  **Definition 3.3** The inverse of this matrix is the **[mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] point Fourier Matrix** .  [mathjax]\\mathbf{W}_N^{-1} = \\mathbf{F}_N = \\frac{1}{N}\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 & \\cdots & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & \\overline{\\omega } & \\overline{\\omega }^2 & \\cdots & \\overline{\\omega }^{N-1} \\\\\\ 1 & \\overline{\\omega }^2 & \\overline{\\omega }^4 & \\cdots & \\overline{\\omega }^{2(N-1)} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & & \\vdots \\\\\\ 1 & \\overline{\\omega }^{N-1} & \\overline{\\omega }^{2(N-1)} & \\cdots & \\overline{\\omega }^{(N-1)(N-1)} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Definition 3.4** We say that the vector  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} c_0 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ c_{N-1} \\end{pmatrix}= \\mathbf{F}_N \\begin{pmatrix} y_0 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ y_{N-1} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is the **Finite Discrete Fourier Transform (FDFT)** of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} y_0 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ y_{N-1} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  (Note that the Discrete Fourier Transform is the periodic, continuous function obtained by imagining that we take these coefficients and sum the continuous functions, allowing it to be defined for all times [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].)  Discrete Fourier Transform", "filename": "DFTLab-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Discrete Fourier Transform"}

{"pageid": 91, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab13", "text": "### Even and odd symmetry    * A function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **even** if [mathjaxinline]f(-t)=f(t)[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].     * A function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **odd** if [mathjaxinline]f(-t)=-f(t)[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].   If  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty a_n \\cos nt + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty b_n \\sin nt,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      then substituting [mathjaxinline]-t[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(-t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty a_n \\cos nt + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty (-b_n) \\sin nt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      The right hand sides match if and only if [mathjaxinline]b_n=0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].  **Conclusion:** The Fourier series of an even function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] has only cosine terms (including the constant term):  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty a_n \\cos nt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Similarly, the Fourier series of an odd function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] has only sine terms:  [mathjax]f(t) = \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty b_n \\sin nt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Fourier series of Square wave using oddness  The square wave,  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\begin{cases} 1 & 0 < t < \\pi \\\\\\ -1 & -\\pi < t < 0 \\end{cases},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is an odd function, so  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\sum _{n=1}^\\infty b_n \\sin nt[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some numbers [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline]. The Fourier coefficient formula says  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_n[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi \\underbrace{\\mathrm{Sq}(t) \\sin nt}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{even}}} } \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{2}{\\pi } \\int _{0}^\\pi \\mathrm{Sq}(t) \\sin nt \\, dt \\qquad \\text{(the two halves of the integral are equal, by symmetry)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{2}{\\pi } \\int _{0}^\\pi \\sin nt \\, dt \\qquad (\\text{since } \\mathrm{Sq}(t)=1 \\text{ whenever } 0 < t < \\pi )[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\left. \\frac{2(-\\cos nt)}{\\pi n} \\right|_{0}^\\pi[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{2}{\\pi n} ( -\\cos n\\pi + \\cos 0 )[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\begin{cases} \\frac{4}{\\pi n}, & \\text{ if } n \\text{ is odd,} \\\\\\ 0, & \\text{ if } n \\text{ is even.} \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Thus  [mathjax]b_1 = \\frac{4}{\\pi },\\quad b_3 = \\frac{4}{3\\pi },\\quad b_5=\\frac{4}{5\\pi }, \\dots[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and all other Fourier coefficients are [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  **Conclusion:**  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\left( \\sin t + \\frac{\\sin 3t}{3} + \\frac{\\sin 5t}{5} + \\cdots \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Symmetry", "filename": "introtofourier-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Symmetry"}

{"pageid": 92, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab8", "text": "In order to determine how the load will affect beam bending, we need to understand all of the resultant forces inside of the beam that occur due to external loading.  There are two main resultants that will be important to us.    1. The **shear force** resultant, [mathjaxinline]S(x)[/mathjaxinline]     2. The **bending moment** resultant, [mathjaxinline]M(x)[/mathjaxinline] (equivalent to torque)   To gain some intuition for these forces, we will look at a toy example of a long slender beam, where we have hung a heavy object off the one end.  ![Beam pinned at one end with heavy mass on other end](/static/images/beamderiv_3.svg)    If you were to cut the beam near the weight, the beam would fall. So what this tells us is that there is a force internal to the beam that is preventing the force of the mass from causing the beam to fall off. That is, internal to the beam, there is an equal and opposite resultant force. This is the **shear force** resultant.  ![Shear force on infinitesimal segment of beam](/static/images/beamderiv_4.svg)    **Figure 24** : Shear force [mathjaxinline]S[/mathjaxinline] with positive orientation on infinitesimal slice of beam      On an infinitesimal slice of beam, we draw a positive shear force resultant so that there is a shear force in the upward direction on the right, and the corresponding downward facing shear force on the left.  In our toy example, the shear force resultant is constant along the beam, exactly canceling the effect of the weight in order to hold it up. However, that is not the only thing happening. Because if we hold the beam further and further from the point where the mass is hung, we not only have to apply a vertical shear force, but the further away our point of contact, the force also creates a torque, and the beam must supply a resultant torque (or **bending moment** as it is called in the mechanics of beams) to prevent the beam from rotating.  ![Bending moment on infinitesimal segment of beam](/static/images/beamderiv_5.svg)    **Figure 25** : Bending moment [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] with positive orientation on an infinitesimal slice of beam      Positive bending moments are drawn so that they bend the beam in the direction that causes it to look like a smile.  The more the beam is trying to curve, the more bending moment must be applied to counter the rotation. In our toy example, we see that the further we are from the applied shear force, the more moment we need to counteract the effect. Thus we have a relationship between the bending moment and the shear force  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx}M(x) = -S(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Additionally, the bending moment is exactly what causes the beam to bend. Thus it is proportional to the curvature, and the relationship between the bending moment and the curvature is given by  [mathjax]M(x) = EI \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline] depends on the material of the beam, and [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] is the moment of inertia, which depends on the geometry of the beam. Now that we have all of the forces, we can finally write down our model.  ### How are resultant forces affected by a distributed load?  Suppose that along our beam, we have some distributed load [mathjaxinline]q_y(x)[/mathjaxinline] (units of [Force]/[Length]), where the subscript [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is used to denote the fact that the positive direction points in the positive [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] direction.  ![Beam with distributed load](/static/images/beamderiv_6.svg)    **Figure 26** : Beam with distributed load [mathjaxinline]q_y(x)[/mathjaxinline] in positive orientation (pointing up).      To see how this load affects the resultant forces inside the beam, we need to do a force and torque balance on an infinitesimal segment of our beam.  ![Distributed load, shear forces, and bending moments on slice of beam](/static/images/beamderiv_7.svg)    **Figure 27** : Load, shear forces, and bending moments on a slice of beam of width [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline].      On an infinitesimal segment of beam of width [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline], we can assume that the load is the constant value [mathjaxinline]q_y(x)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus the total force is [mathjaxinline]q_y(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]. Force balance tells us that  [mathjax]S(x+dx) - S(x) + q_y(x) \\, dx = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Dividing by [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] and taking the limits as [mathjaxinline]dx \\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline], this gives us  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx}S(x) = -q_y(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, using the fact that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}M(x) = -S(x)[/mathjaxinline], we can rewrite this as  [mathjax]q_y(x) = - \\frac{d}{dx}S(x) = \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}M(x) = \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}\\left(EI \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2} \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In the case that the material and geometry of the beam are constant throughout, this reduces to the fourth order differential equation relating the deflection of the beam to the external loading  [mathjax]\\boxed {EI \\frac{d^4v(x)}{dx^4} = q_y(x). }[/mathjax]|   ---|---  The nitty gritty", "filename": "bvp-tab8-text2.html", "title": "The nitty gritty"}

{"pageid": 94, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab10", "text": "In real life, there is always damping, and this prevents the runaway growth in the pure resonance scenario of the previous section.  **Problem 10.1** Describe the steady state solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 0.1 \\dot{x} + 49 x = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Remark 10.2** The term [mathjaxinline]0.1 \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] is the damping term.  Recall: The steady state solution is the periodic solution. (Other solutions will be a sum of the steady state solution with a transient solution solving the homogeneous ODE  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 0.1 \\dot{x} + 49 x = 0;[/mathjax]|   ---|---      these transient solutions tend to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline], because the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial are positive (in fact, this is an underdamped system).  **Solution:** First let's solve  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 0.1 \\dot{x} + 49 x = \\sin nt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Before doing that, solve the complex replacement ODE  [mathjax]\\ddot{z} + 0.1 \\dot{z} + 49 z = e^{int}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2 + 0.1 r + 49[/mathjaxinline], so ERF gives  [mathjax]z = \\frac{1}{P(in)} e^{int} = \\frac{1}{(49-n^2) + (0.1 n)i} e^{int},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with complex gain [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{(49-n^2) + (0.1 n)i}[/mathjaxinline] and gain  [mathjax]g_n \\colon =\\frac{1}{\\left|(49-n^2) + (0.1 n)i\\right|}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus  [mathjax]x = \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left( \\frac{1}{(49-n^2) + (0.1 n)i} e^{int} \\right);[/mathjax]|   ---|---      this is a sinusoid of amplitude [mathjaxinline]g_n[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]x = g_n \\cos (nt-\\phi _n)[/mathjaxinline] for some [mathjaxinline]\\phi _n[/mathjaxinline].  The input signal  [mathjax]\\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1, \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin nt}{n},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      elicits the system response  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\sum _{n \\ge 1, \\text{ odd}} g_n \\frac{\\cos (nt-\\phi _n)}{n}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx {\\color{blue}{0.021}} \\cos (t-\\phi _1) + 0.008 \\cos (3t-\\phi _3) + 0.008 \\cos (5t-\\phi _5)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\quad + {\\color{orange}{0.204}} \\cos (7t-\\phi _7) + 0.003 \\cos (9t-\\phi _9) + \\text{(even smaller terms)}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Conclusion:** The system response is almost indistinguishable from a pure sinusoid of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]7[/mathjaxinline].  Resonance with Damping", "filename": "solveodes-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Resonance with Damping"}

{"pageid": 95, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab4", "text": "The **Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)** is an algorithm originated by Cooley and Tukey in 1965 for computing the FDFT very efficiently.  Note that if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is an [mathjaxinline]N\\times N[/mathjaxinline] matrix, and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]N\\times 1[/mathjaxinline], to compute [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}y[/mathjaxinline] requires [mathjaxinline]N^2[/mathjaxinline] scalar multiplications in general.  We reduce this by taking advantage of the symmetries in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}_N[/mathjaxinline].  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]N = 2^j[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline] a positive integer.  FFT is a divide and conquer algorithm, which exploits the fact that  [mathjax]\\mathbf{F}_N y = \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf{I}_{N/2} & \\mathbf{D}_{N/2}\\\\\\ \\mathbf{I}_{N/2} & -\\mathbf{D}_{N/2}\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf{F}_{N/2} & 0\\\\\\ 0 & \\mathbf{F}_{N/2}\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\\\\\ y_3 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ y_{N/2-1} \\\\\\ y_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ y_N/2 \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{I}_{N/2}[/mathjaxinline] is the [mathjaxinline]N/2 \\times N/2[/mathjaxinline] identity matrix, and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{D}_{N/2}[/mathjaxinline] is the diagonal matrix  [mathjax]\\mathbf{D}_{N/2} = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & & & & \\\\\\ & \\overline{\\omega } & & & \\\\\\ & & \\overline{\\omega }^2 & & \\\\\\ & & & \\ddots & \\\\\\ & & & & \\overline{\\omega }^{N/2} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We continue to apply the same rule to the two [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}_{N/2}[/mathjaxinline] matrices to get a formula for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}_N[/mathjaxinline] involving four [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}_{N/4}[/mathjaxinline] matrix multiplications instead.  Continue.  **Result** We can compute [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}_N y[/mathjaxinline] with only [mathjaxinline]\\frac12 Nj = \\frac12 N \\log N[/mathjaxinline] multiplications!  FFT", "filename": "DFTLab-tab4-text1.html", "title": "FFT"}

{"pageid": 96, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab9", "text": "The mathlet below helps you to visualize solutions to the differential equation  [mathjax]\\ddot x + \\omega _0^2 x =\\omega _0^2 f(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In this applet the function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] has a fixed angular frequency of 1. That is, the input signal is [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic. But, you can choose what [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic function it is:    * a sine wave [mathjaxinline]\\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline],     * the square wave of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline],     * the sawtooth wave of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], or     * a [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic impulse train.   You can adjust the natural frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] of the system using the slider. Thus the slider adjusts the resonant frequency of the system.  Choose [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] to be the sine wave. Look at what happens as you change [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline]. Why does the amplitude of the response go to infinity when [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0 =1[/mathjaxinline]?  Now choose [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] to be the square wave. Notice that the amplitude of the response becomes infinite at [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] = 1, 3 or 5.  **Question 9.1** As [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] gets close to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline], or [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] what is the dominant frequency in the output?  ###  Answer  You should have seen that with [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] near 1 the output resembles a frequency 1 sine wave. For [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] near 3 the dominant frequency in the output is 3, i.e. there are three peaks in the oscillation over one cycle of the square wave. Likewise for [mathjaxinline]\\omega _0[/mathjaxinline] near 5 the dominant frequency is 5.  We can explain this using Fourier series. The square wave has Fourier series  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\sum _{n\\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin nt}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Each term in the series affects the system. If the system has natural frequency (very) close to 3 then the [mathjaxinline]\\sin 3t[/mathjaxinline] term resonates with a large amplitude. Thus, the response to that term is far larger than the response to any other term.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Harmonic Frequency Applet", "filename": "solveodes-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Harmonic Frequency Applet"}

{"pageid": 97, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab1", "text": "### Objectives    * Find the smallest **period** of any periodic function.     * Find the **Fourier coefficients** of a periodic function of period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].     * Determine the **Fourier series** of the **square wave.**    * Simplify Fourier series computations of **even and odd periodic functions** by identifying which coefficients must be zero automatically. {"pageid": 98, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab5", "text": "**Problem 5.1** If the system response of [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\sin nt}{50-n^2}[/mathjaxinline], for which input signal [mathjaxinline]\\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] is the gain the largest?  **Solution:** The gain is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left| \\frac{1}{50-n^2} \\right|[/mathjaxinline], which is largest when [mathjaxinline]|50-n^2|[/mathjaxinline] is smallest. This happens for [mathjaxinline]n=7[/mathjaxinline].  The gain for [mathjaxinline]\\sin 7t[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], and the next largest gain, occurring for [mathjaxinline]\\sin 6t[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin 8t[/mathjaxinline], is [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{14}[/mathjaxinline]. Thus the system approximately filters out all the Fourier components of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] except for the [mathjaxinline]\\sin 7t[/mathjaxinline] term.  **Problem 5.2** Let [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] be the periodic solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 50 x = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Which Fourier coefficient of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is largest? Which is second largest?  **Solution:** The input signal  [mathjax]\\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1, \\text{ odd}} \\frac{\\sin nt}{n}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      elicits the system response  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1, \\text{ odd}} \\left(\\frac{1}{50-n^2}\\right) \\frac{\\sin nt}{n}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{0.020}} \\sin t + 0.008 \\sin 3t + 0.008 \\sin 5t + {\\color{orange}{0.143}} \\sin 7t - 0.004 \\sin 9t - \\text{(even smaller terms)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so the coefficient of [mathjaxinline]\\sin 7t[/mathjaxinline] is largest, and the coefficient of [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] is second largest. (This makes sense since the Fourier coefficient [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{(50-n^2)n}[/mathjaxinline] is large only when one of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]50-n^2[/mathjaxinline] is small.)  **Remark 5.3** Even though the system response is a complicated Fourier series, with infinitely many terms, only one or two are significant, and the rest are negligible.  ![Pure sinusoid of the largest term](/static/images/u6s3_largesttermplot.svg)| ![Sum of first two largest terms](/static/images/u6s3_firsttwoterms.svg)   ---|---   ![Sum of first five terms](/static/images/u6s3_firstfiveterms.svg)| ![Sum of first 100 terms](/static/images/u6s3_first100terms.svg)  Near Resonance", "filename": "solveodes-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Near Resonance"}

{"pageid": 99, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab4", "text": "You might be wondering how we can use Fourier series, series composed of continuous functions, to approximate a discontinuous function. While it's true that we can get a Fourier series that converges to a function with discontinuities, the convergence fails at the discontinuities, and near points of discontinuity **the convergence is very slow** and very peculiar. Namely, the **partial sums** of the Fourier series overshoot and undershoot the values of the function near these points of discontinuity. This is known as the **Gibbs' Phenomenon** . All discontinuous functions exhibit Gibbs' phenomenon.  We illustrate this phenomenon using the example of the square wave of height [mathjaxinline]\\pi / 4[/mathjaxinline] \u2014 which we denote by [mathjaxinline]S\\left(t\\right) = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. In this case the discontinuities are at the integer multiples of [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. The Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]S\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle S\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}\\left(t\\right) = \\sin t + \\frac{1}{3} \\sin 3t + \\frac{1}{5} \\sin 5t + \\cdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\sum _{n \\textrm{ odd}}^{\\infty } \\frac{1}{n} \\sin nt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      For an odd positive integer [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline], write [mathjaxinline]S_{N}\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] for the [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline]th **partial sum**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle S_{N}\\left(t\\right) \\colon =\\sum _{n \\textrm{ odd}}^{N} \\frac{1}{n} \\sin nt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Then [mathjaxinline]S\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] is the limit of the functions [mathjaxinline]S_{N}\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]N \\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. It turns out that it is possible to do a calculation that's a little bit beyond the scope of this class that for [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] very large, [mathjaxinline]S_{N}[/mathjaxinline] overshoots [mathjaxinline]\\pi / 4[/mathjaxinline] (or undershoots [mathjaxinline]-\\pi / 4[/mathjaxinline]) at a point of discontinuity by about [mathjaxinline]9 \\%[/mathjaxinline]. This overshooting and undershooting can easily be seen in the figures below.  ![ ](/static/images/Gibbs.svg)  **Figure 7** : The partial sum functions [mathjaxinline]S_{N}\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]N = 7, 13, 25, 49[/mathjaxinline].      This overshoot/undershoot by about 9% happens **always** , not just for the case of [mathjaxinline]S(t)[/mathjaxinline], but for any function with discontinuities. In practice, one can only generate approximate Fourier series (with only a finite number of Fourier coefficients, known with some error). Thus the poor convergence of Fourier series for functions with discontinuities \u2014 and particularly the Gibb's phenomenon \u2014 creates (serious) difficulties in areas such as signal processing.  The intuitive reason that the approximation [mathjaxinline]S_N[/mathjaxinline] behaves so poorly near discontinuities is that [mathjaxinline]S_N[/mathjaxinline] is continuous (it is a finite sum of continuous functions). A continuous function cannot perfectly approximate a discontinuous one. A confusing point, is that even though for [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] arbitrarily large, the function [mathjaxinline]S_{N}[/mathjaxinline] acts poorly at the discontinuity, the series [mathjaxinline]\\sum _{n \\textrm{odd}}^{\\infty } \\frac{1}{n} \\sin nt[/mathjaxinline] doesn't. This illustrates how limits can act strangely sometimes, as well as the fact that the convergence of [mathjaxinline]S_{N}\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]S\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] \u201cdoesn't happen in the best possible way\". If you're interested in questions like this, you might find 18.311 or 18.100 interesting.  **Mathlet exploration**  In the mathlet below, choose the Target function [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline], which is the [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic function which is defined by [mathjaxinline]D(t) = t/2[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < t< \\pi[/mathjaxinline]. This function has Fourier series  [mathjax]\\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } \\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}\\sin (nt).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Select \u201csine terms\" move the sliders to match the Fourier coefficients. Observe how the first few terms approximate the function near the discontinuity.  Note that you can find the Fourier series of more functions and observe the Gibbs' phenomenon (or not if the target is continuous) by selecting different target functions. Click on the **Distance** checkbox. Find the coefficients by using the sliders to minimize the root mean squared **Distance** between the sum of the first few terms in the series and the target function.  Gibbs' Phenomenon", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Gibbs' Phenomenon"}

{"pageid": 100, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab11", "text": "We can extend the model for beam bending to a model of a horizontal beam that has a distributed load [mathjaxinline]q_u(x)[/mathjaxinline], a deflection of [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline], and an axial load [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] via the equation [mathjax]EI\\frac{d^4}{dx^4}v(x)+F\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}v(x) = q_y(x).[/mathjax]| ---|--- When the axial loading is zero, this reduces to the beam bending equation we derived previously.

{"pageid": 101, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab9", "text": "Recall that the average value of a function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] on an interval [mathjaxinline]\\, (a, b) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be the area under the curve over that interval, divided by the length of that interval:  [mathjax]\\text{ave}(f) := \\frac{\\int _a^b f(t) \\, dt}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The constant term of the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\frac{a_0}{2} = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\, dt = \\frac{\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\, dt}{\\pi - (-\\pi )},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which is the average value of [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] on the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, (-\\pi ,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 9.1**  Find the constant term of the [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic function  [mathjax]f(t) = \\begin{cases} t, & 0 < t < \\pi \\\\\\ 0, & -\\pi < t < 0 \\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:** The average value of this function over one period is given by the area under the curve, divided by the length of the interval, which in this case is [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. By sketching the function over the interval [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < t < \\pi[/mathjaxinline],  ![See caption](/static/images/u6_periodic_2pi_secondexample_2.svg)    **Figure 4** : The graph of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] over the interval [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < t < \\pi[/mathjaxinline].      we can compute the area under the curve directly to find the average value, which is  [mathjax]\\frac{(1/2)\\pi ^2}{2\\pi } = \\frac{\\pi }{4}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Meaning of the constant term", "filename": "introtofourier-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Meaning of the constant term"}

{"pageid": 103, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab9", "text": "You can use a Fourier series expansion any time you have a function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] defined on a finite interval [mathjaxinline][0,L][/mathjaxinline]. First you create a periodic extension of this function defined everywhere, and then find the Fourier series of the periodic function. (In order to simplify the Fourier series, we typically choose to extend our function to be either even or odd, so that we end up with a cosine or sine series.)  **Example 9.1** Consider the function [mathjaxinline]f(t) = t^2[/mathjaxinline] defined on the interval [mathjaxinline][0,1][/mathjaxinline].  The even periodic extension is the period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] function defined by  [mathjax]f(t) = t^2, \\quad -1 \\leq t \\leq 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![Plot of even extension](/static/images/u6_even_extension.svg)      The odd periodic extension is the period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] function defined by  [mathjax]f(t) = \\begin{cases} t^2 & 0 < t < 1 \\\\\\ -t^2 & -1 < t < 0 \\end{cases}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ![Plot of odd extension](/static/images/u6_odd_extension.svg)      Periodic extensions", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Periodic extensions"}

{"pageid": 105, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab10", "text": "### Extending d'Alembert's solution to finite intervals  It turns out that you can use the d'Alembert idea to solve the wave equation on finite intervals [mathjaxinline][0, L][/mathjaxinline] as well. The main idea is to take the initial conditions for the initial position and velocity, which are only defined for [mathjaxinline]0 < x < L[/mathjaxinline] and extend these to either even or odd **[mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline]-periodic** functions defined for all [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] that are consistent with the specified boundary conditions. You will recover exactly the functions we found using Fourier's method (but expressed in a slightly different form). {"pageid": 106, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab3", "text": "Suppose we have the same spring-mass system as the initial value problem you just solved. However, instead of specifying the initial position and velocity, we want to specify different conditions at different points in time.  The mass is initially at the origin at time [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline], but now we are interested in finding a solution that ensures the mass passes through the point [mathjaxinline]x=1[/mathjaxinline] at some later time [mathjaxinline]t=t_1[/mathjaxinline]. The governing differential equation is the same  [mathjax]\\frac{d^2}{dt^2} x + 4x = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      But now we are interested in finding a solution on a time interval [mathjaxinline]0 \\leq t \\leq t_1[/mathjaxinline], where we impose a condition at each end of the interval:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t_1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We call these conditions **boundary conditions.**  This type of problem is known as a **boundary value problem,** or **BVP** for short.  **Solution:** The general solution is the same as for the initial value problem:  [mathjax]x(t) = A\\cos (2t)+B\\sin (2t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We find [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] by substituting in [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t=t_1[/mathjaxinline], and solving the equations.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\cos (0)+B\\sin (0) , \\qquad \\longrightarrow A=0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t_1) = 1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle B\\sin (2t_1), \\qquad \\longrightarrow B = \\frac{1}{\\sin (2t_1)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The solution to this boundary value problem is  [mathjax]x(t) = \\frac{\\sin (2t)}{\\sin (2t_1)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Observe that this solution only makes sense for values of [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\sin (2t_1)\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline]. For example, when [mathjaxinline]t_1 = \\pi /2[/mathjaxinline], this boundary value problem does not have a solution at all!  A new feature of boundary value problems is that they need not obey existence and uniqueness. There are three possibilities:    1. The boundary value problem has a unique solution.     2. The boundary value problem has no solution.     3. The boundary value problem has infinitely many solutions.   In this example, you see a failure of existence for [mathjaxinline]t_1 = n\\pi /2[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]n=1,2,3,\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline]. However, the solution exists and is unique for values of [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\sin (2t_1)\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline].  Text about the video", "filename": "bvp-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Text about the video"}

{"pageid": 107, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab13", "text": "Here's an idea: Euler's formula  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{it} = \\cos t + i \\sin t[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---      tells us that complex exponentials can be written as a sum of a sine and a cosine function. This suggests that we might be able to write a Fourier series  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_{0}}{2} + \\sum _{n = 1}^{\\infty } \\left(a_{n} \\cos nt + b_{n} \\sin nt\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      with real coefficients [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] as a series of complex exponentials [mathjaxinline]\\sum _{n = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c_{n} e^{i n t}[/mathjaxinline], for some **complex** coefficients [mathjaxinline]c_{n}[/mathjaxinline]. As it turns out, this is true, that is, we can always write a Fourier series in terms of complex exponentials. Since the two series turn out to be equal, we'll also call the series in terms of complex exponentials a Fourier series.  So let's walk through the process of converting a series of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{a_{0}}{2} + \\sum _{n = 1}^{\\infty } \\left(a_{n} \\cos nt + b_{n} \\sin nt\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      to a series of the form [mathjaxinline]\\sum _{n = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c_{n} e^{i n t}[/mathjaxinline].  **Step 1: Rewriting the sum.**  Using Euler's formula and the fact that [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] is an odd function and [mathjaxinline]\\cos t[/mathjaxinline] is an even function, we notice that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin t = \\frac{i}{2} \\left(e^{-it} - e^{it}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos t = \\frac{1}{2} \\left(e^{it} + e^{-it}\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Then we see that given any Fourier series [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], we can write  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_{0}}{2} + \\sum _{n = 1}^{\\infty } \\left(a_{n} \\cos nt + b_{n} \\sin nt\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_{0}}{2} + \\sum _{n = 1}^{\\infty } \\left(\\frac{a_{n}}{2} \\left(e^{i n t} + e^{-i n t}\\right) + \\frac{i b_{n}}{2} \\left(e^{-i n t} - e^{i n t}\\right)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_{0}}{2} + \\frac{1}{2} \\sum _{n = 1}^{\\infty } \\left(\\left(a_{n} - i b_{n}\\right) e^{i n t} + \\left(a_{n} + i b_{n}\\right) e^{-i n t} \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Step 2: Defining coefficients.**  We can see that [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] can be written as a sum of complex exponentials. Let's write the coefficients of these exponentials nicely so that we can easily convert back and forth between the two forms. Define [mathjaxinline]c_{0} \\colon =a_{0} / 2[/mathjaxinline]. For [mathjaxinline]n > 0[/mathjaxinline], define  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_{n} \\colon =\\frac{a_{n} - i b_{n}}{2},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_{-n} \\colon =\\bar{c}_{n} = \\frac{a_{n} + i b_{n}}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Then we can write [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] compactly as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f\\left(t\\right) = \\sum _{n = -\\infty }^{\\infty } c_{n} e^{i n t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Step 3: Relating coefficients to inner products.**  ### Remark about inner products:  Note that for real valued [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic functions [mathjaxinline]\\, f \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, g \\,[/mathjaxinline] we define an inner product as  [mathjax]\\left\\langle f, g \\right\\rangle = \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\cdot g \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]\\, f \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, g \\,[/mathjaxinline] are complex valued functions, we must define the inner product as  [mathjax]\\left\\langle f, g \\right\\rangle = \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\cdot \\overline{g} \\, dt,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\overline{g} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is the complex conjugate of [mathjaxinline]\\, g \\,[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 13.1**  [mathjax]\\left\\langle e^{int}, e^{int} \\right\\rangle = \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } e^{int}\\cdot e^{-int} \\, dt = \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } dt = 2\\pi .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]m \\neq n[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left\\langle e^{int}, e^{imt} \\right\\rangle[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } e^{int}\\cdot e^{-imt} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } e^{i(n-m)t}\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left. \\frac{e^{i(n-m)t}}{i(n-m)} \\right|_{-\\pi }^{\\pi }[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^{i(n-m)\\pi } - e^{-i(n-m)\\pi }}{i(n-m)} = \\frac{2}{n-m}\\sin ((n-m)\\pi ) = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore the [mathjaxinline]e^{int}[/mathjaxinline] are orthogonal.  In particular, notice that for [mathjaxinline]n>0[/mathjaxinline], we can compute [mathjaxinline]c_n[/mathjaxinline] by the formula  [mathjax]c_n = \\frac{\\left\\langle f , e^{int}\\right\\rangle }{\\left\\langle e^{int} , e^{int} \\right\\rangle }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This definition is in agreement with the definition of [mathjaxinline]c_n = \\frac{a_n - ib_n}{2}[/mathjaxinline]. (You can check this!)  ###  Check worked out  Notice that for [mathjaxinline]n > 0[/mathjaxinline],  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_{n}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_{n} - i b_{n}}{2} = \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\left(t\\right) \\cos nt \\, dt - \\frac{i}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi }f\\left(t\\right) \\sin nt \\, dt \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\left(t\\right) \\left(\\cos nt - i \\sin nt\\right) dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\left(t\\right) \\left(\\cos \\left(-nt\\right) + i \\sin \\left(-nt\\right)\\right) dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\left(t\\right) e^{-i n t} dt = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\left\\langle f , e^{int} \\right\\rangle[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\left\\langle f , e^{int}\\right\\rangle }{\\left\\langle e^{int} , e^{int} \\right\\rangle }.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   An analagous computation shows that for any [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_{n} = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f\\left(t\\right) e^{-i n t} dt = \\frac{\\left\\langle f , e^{int}\\right\\rangle }{\\left\\langle e^{int} , e^{int} \\right\\rangle }.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Key properties of complex Fourier series**    * Often integrals involving complex exponentials are actually much easier to compute than integrals involving sines and cosines.     * We can also make sense of Fourier series of complex-valued functions more easily in this setting.   Complex Fourier Series", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Complex Fourier Series"}

{"pageid": 112, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab1", "text": "### Objectives  In this laboratory, we explore how signals are sampled in the real world, and the mathematics that allows us to determine the frequencies from sampled data.  After this laboratory, you will be able to    * Apply the Discrete Fourier Transform to real signals.     * Modify signals by manipulating signal data in the frequency spectrum.     * Identify notes and harmonics in frequency spectrum coming from musical audio files.     * Read frequency information from Spectrograms of audio files that change in time. {"pageid": 113, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab7", "text": "###  Proof of orthogonality  Here we prove that if [mathjaxinline]m\\neq n[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos (nt)[/mathjaxinline] are orthogonal to [mathjaxinline]\\sin (mt)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos (mt)[/mathjaxinline]. To do this we use that fact that both [mathjaxinline]\\sin (nt)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos (nt)[/mathjaxinline] solve the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + n^2 x = 0[/mathjaxinline], and both [mathjaxinline]\\sin (mt)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos (mt)[/mathjaxinline] solve the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + m^2 x = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Supose that [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] solves the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + n^2 x = 0[/mathjaxinline]. And suppose [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] solves the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + m^2 x = 0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]n\\neq m[/mathjaxinline].  Then in particular  [mathjax]\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\ddot u(t) v(t) \\, dt \\phantom{\\int } =\\left.\\phantom{\\int } \\dot u(t) v(t)\\right|_{-\\pi }^{\\pi } - \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\dot u(t) \\dot v(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that [mathjaxinline]\\left. \\dot u(t) v(t)\\right|_{-\\pi }^{\\pi } = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Both [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] are both periodic on [mathjaxinline](-\\pi ,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline], therefore so is [mathjaxinline]\\dot u(t) v(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the difference [mathjaxinline]\\dot u(\\pi )v(\\pi )-\\dot u(-\\pi )v(-\\pi ) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Thus this reduces to the expression  [mathjax]\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\ddot u(t) v(t) \\, dt = - \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\dot u(t) \\dot v(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      A similar argument shows that  [mathjax]\\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } u(t) \\ddot v(t) \\, dt = - \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } \\dot u(t) \\dot v(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      However, by using the substitution from the differential equation, we have that [mathjaxinline]\\ddot u(t) = -n^2u(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ddot v(t) = -m^2 v(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore it follows that  [mathjax]n^2 \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } u(t) v(t) \\, dt = m^2 \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } u(t) v(t) \\, dt .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that since we have assumed that [mathjaxinline]m\\neq n[/mathjaxinline], the only way for this to hold is for the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } u(t) v(t) \\, dt = 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Remark 7.1** In disguise, this is the same as showing that two eigenvectors corresponding to distinct eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Proof of orthogonality", "filename": "introtofourier-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Proof of orthogonality"}

{"pageid": 115, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab11", "text": "The Diffusion Equation governs the evolution of the [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] concentration profile inside of the length of the pipe. Our pipe is a finite length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline]. How do we handle what happens at either end of the pipe?  We need to specify the initial condition, i.e. the initial concentration distribution of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]u_0 = u(x,0),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and constraints that tell us what the boundary condtions are at all positive times.  **Question 11.1** What are the boundary conditions? What can we specify?  The most natural thing to prescribe in a **physical** sense would be the flow rate of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] into/out of the ends of the pipe: [mathjaxinline]-\\alpha \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}(0,t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-\\alpha \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}(L,t)[/mathjaxinline]. Another, less physically intuitive example in this case, but which will be mathematically simpler, is the case where the [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] concentration is prescribed at each end of the pipe: [mathjaxinline]u(0,t)=c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u(L,t)=c_2[/mathjaxinline]. We can imagine this is due to the pipe connecting into a large reservoir of constant concentration; even as [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] flows into and out of the pipe, the reservoir is so large that its net concentration remains constant. This could be represented as a large tank in a brewery with small pipes attached, for example.  ###  Side Note: Fluid vs. Cell Flow  It is important to note that for the model created above, we are only considering the diffusion of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] in a non-flowing liquid, and **not** the transport of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] by the flow of the liquid itself. Such a process is called advection, and is modeled by a different set of partial differential equations. Also, one can combine both of these methods of transport, and this results in a partial differential equation called the Advection-Diffusion Equation. For now we will assume that the fluid is near- stationary so that all the transport is dominated by diffusion, so we will be fine using the Diffusion Equation for our models.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Physical Boundary Conditions", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Physical Boundary Conditions"}

{"pageid": 116, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**  After this section and some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand why **boundary value problems** do not satisfy the **existence and uniqueness theorem.**    * Solve simple boundary value problems with specified **boundary conditions.**  Objectives", "filename": "bvp-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 117, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab7", "text": "We can solve the same differential equation in general for a periodic input signal of any frequency.  Solve the differential equation  [mathjax]\\ddot x +\\omega _0^2 x = f(t),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]2L[/mathjaxinline]-periodic, and has Fourier series  [mathjax]f(t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum _{n=1}^{\\infty } \\left( a_n\\cos (\\omega _n t) + b_n\\sin (\\omega _n t) \\right), \\qquad \\text{where }\\omega _n = \\frac{n\\pi }{L}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      A particular solution is given by  [mathjax]\\boxed {\\displaystyle x_p(t) =\\frac{a_0}{2\\omega _0^2} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} \\frac{a_n \\cos \\omega _n t}{\\omega _0^2-\\omega _n^2} + \\frac{b_n \\sin \\omega _n t}{\\omega _0^2-\\omega _n^2} }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  In general", "filename": "solveodes-tab7-text1.html", "title": "In general"}

{"pageid": 118, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab10", "text": "**Key Insight :** if a function is differentiable, you can simply differentiate its Fourier series term by term to obtain the Fourier series for the derivative.  ###  Note:  There are many subtle, but important, questions in Fourier series that we will not cover here (but which courses such as 18.100 (Real Analysis) do, at least partially). For example: If I write some arbitrary Fourier series, how do I know if it comes from a differentiable function? If I differentiate term by term the Fourier series for a function that is not differentiable (like the square wave function), is the result the Fourier series for something?  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 10.1** The Fourier series for the period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] triangle wave is:  [mathjax]g(t) = \\frac{\\pi }{2} - \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\left(\\cos t + \\frac{\\cos 3t}{3^2} + \\frac{\\cos 5t}{5^2} + \\dotsb \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      What is [mathjaxinline]g'(t)[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Solution  Differentiating the Fourier series [mathjaxinline]\\, g(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] term-by-term gives [mathjax]g'(t) = \\frac{4}{\\pi }\\left(\\sin t + \\frac{\\sin 3t}{3} + \\frac{\\sin 5t}{5} + \\ldots \\right),[/mathjax]|   ---|---   which is the Fourier series of the [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic square wave!  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Differentiating Fourier Series", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Differentiating Fourier Series"}

{"pageid": 119, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab2", "text": "Recall that the exponential response formula gives us a quick method for finding the particular solution to any linear, constant coefficient, differential equations whose input can be expressed in terms of an exponential function.  **The exponential response formula (ERF):** Let [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a polynomial with real, constant coefficients, [mathjaxinline]\\, D = \\frac{d}{dt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] a differential operator, and [mathjaxinline]\\, r \\,[/mathjaxinline] a (real or complex) number. If [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) \\neq 0 \\,[/mathjaxinline], then a particular solution to the inhomogeneous differential equation  [mathjax]P(D)y = e^{rt} \\qquad \\text{is given by} \\qquad y_p = \\frac{e^{rt}}{P(r)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Caveat   ****Caveat: If [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) = P'(r) = P^{\\prime \\prime }(r) = \\dotsc =P^{(k-1)}(r)= 0\\,[/mathjaxinline], but [mathjaxinline]\\, P^{(k)}(r)\\neq 0 \\,[/mathjaxinline], then a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)y = e^{rt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjax]y_p = \\frac{t^ke^{rt}}{P^{(k)}(r)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ### Sinusoidal input:  [mathjaxinline]P(D)x = \\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] |  is the real part of |  [mathjaxinline]P(D)z = e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline];   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]P(D)x = \\sin (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] |  is the imaginary part of |  [mathjaxinline]P(D)z = e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline].      Therefore    * a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)x = \\cos (\\omega t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left[\\frac{e^{i\\omega t}}{P(i\\omega )} \\right]\\,[/mathjaxinline];     * a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D)x = \\sin (\\omega t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle x_p = \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left[\\frac{e^{i\\omega t}}{P(i\\omega )} \\right]\\,[/mathjaxinline].   Review ERF", "filename": "solveodes-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Review ERF"}

{"pageid": 122, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab2", "text": "The wave equation is a PDE that models light waves, sound waves, waves along a string, etc.  **Problem 2.1** Model a vibrating guitar string.  **Variables and functions:** Define  [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] |  length of the string   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\mu[/mathjaxinline] |  mass per unit length   [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] | **magnitude** of the tension force   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  position along the string (from [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] |  vertical displacement of a point on the string      Here    * [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mu[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] are constants;     * [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] are independent variables; and     * [mathjaxinline]u=u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] is a function defined for [mathjaxinline]x \\in [0,L][/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t \\ge 0[/mathjaxinline]. The vertical displacement is measured relative to the equilibrium position in which the string makes a straight line.   At any given time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], the string is in the shape of the graph of [mathjaxinline]u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  **Assumption:** The string is taut, so the vertical displacement of the string is small, and the slope of the string at any point is small.  Consider the piece of string between positions [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x+\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] be the (small) angle formed by the string and the horizontal line at position [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], and let [mathjaxinline]\\theta + \\Delta \\theta[/mathjaxinline] be the same angle at position [mathjaxinline]x+\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline].  ![Small piece of string](/static/images/vibrating_string.svg)  ###  Derivation of the Wave Equation  Newton's second law says that [mathjaxinline]m \\mathbf\\alpha = \\mathbf{F}[/mathjaxinline]. Taking the vertical component of each side gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{\\mu \\, dx}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{mass}}} } \\underbrace{\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2}}_{{\\color{orange}{\\Large {\\text{acceleration}}}} }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\underbrace{T \\sin (\\theta +d\\theta ) - T \\sin \\theta }_{{\\color{orange}{\\Large {\\text{vertical component of force}}}} }[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = T \\, d(\\sin \\theta ).[/mathjaxinline] | |      Side calculation:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(\\sin \\theta )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\cos \\theta \\, d\\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(\\tan \\theta )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\cos ^2 \\theta } \\, d\\theta ,[/mathjaxinline] |  |      but [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\theta = 1 - \\frac{\\theta ^2}{2!} + \\cdots \\approx 1[/mathjaxinline], so up to a factor that is very close to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] (because we are assuming [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is small), we get  [mathjax]d(\\sin \\theta ) \\approx d\\underbrace{(\\tan \\theta )}_{ {\\color{orange}{\\Large {\\text{slope of string}}}} } = d \\left(\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x} \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Substituting this in gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mu \\, dx \\, \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} \\approx T \\, d \\left(\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x} \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Divide by [mathjaxinline]\\mu \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] to get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx T \\mu ^{-1} \\frac{d \\left(\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x} \\right)}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx T \\mu ^{-1} \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      If we define a new constant [mathjaxinline]c \\colon =\\sqrt{T \\mu ^{-1}}[/mathjaxinline], then this becomes the  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\text{wave equation:}}} \\quad \\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\, \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Note about dimensions:** Observe that [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] is a force, so it has dimension of mass times length over time squared [mathjaxinline][mL/t^2][/mathjaxinline]. And [mathjaxinline]\\mu[/mathjaxinline] is a mass per unit length [mathjaxinline][m/L][/mathjaxinline]. So the constant [mathjaxinline]c=\\sqrt{T/\\mu }[/mathjaxinline] has dimension of [mathjaxinline][L/t][/mathjaxinline] velocity.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The resulting equation describing the evolution of the wave over time is given by the following PDE:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\text{wave equation:}}} \\quad \\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\, \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This makes sense intuitively, since at places where the graph of the string is concave up [mathjaxinline]\\left( \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2} > 0 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] the tension pulling on both sides should combine to produce an upward force, and hence an upward acceleration.  Comparing units of both sides of the wave equation shows that the units for [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]\\text{m}/\\text{s}[/mathjaxinline]. The physical meaning of [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] as a velocity will be explained later.  The ends of a guitar string are fixed, so we have boundary conditions  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(0,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\quad \\text{for all } t \\ge 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u(L,t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\quad \\text{for all } t \\ge 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Vibrating string", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Vibrating string"}

{"pageid": 123, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab8", "text": "Given [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], how do you find the [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline] such that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{a_0}{2} + a_1 \\cos t + a_2 \\cos 2t + a_3 \\cos 3t + \\cdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\quad \\quad + b_1 \\sin t + b_2 \\sin 2t + b_3 \\sin 3t + \\cdots ?[/mathjaxinline] |  |      By the shortcut formulas,  [mathjax]a_n = \\frac{\\langle f, \\cos nt \\rangle }{\\langle \\cos nt,\\cos nt \\rangle } = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\cos nt \\, dt,[/mathjax]|   ---|---   [mathjax]b_n = \\frac{\\langle f, \\sin nt \\rangle }{\\langle \\sin nt,\\sin nt \\rangle } = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\sin nt \\, dt,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the coefficient of [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\frac{a_0}{2} = \\frac{\\langle f, 1 \\rangle }{\\langle 1,1 \\rangle } = \\frac{1}{2\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so  [mathjax]a_0 = \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (Using [mathjaxinline]a_0/2[/mathjaxinline] in the series ensures that the formula for [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]n>0[/mathjaxinline] works also for [mathjaxinline]n=0[/mathjaxinline].) A similar formula holds for [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline].  **Conclusion:** Given [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], its Fourier coefficients can be calculated as follows:  [mathjaxinline]a_n = \\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\cos nt \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]n \\ge 0[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]b_n = \\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\pi } \\int _{-\\pi }^{\\pi } f(t) \\sin nt \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]n \\ge 1[/mathjaxinline].  Fourier coefficient", "filename": "introtofourier-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Fourier coefficient"}

{"pageid": 124, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab8", "text": "**Problem 8.1** Consider the same insulated uniform metal rod as before ([mathjaxinline]\\nu =1[/mathjaxinline], length [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline]) but now assume that the ends are insulated too (instead of exposed and held in ice), and that the initial temperature is given by [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,0)=x[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x \\in (0,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline]. Now what is [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t)[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** As usual, we temporarily forget the initial condition, and use it only at the end.  \u201cInsulated ends\" means that there is zero heat flow through the ends, so the heat flux density function [mathjaxinline]q \\propto -\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial x}[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] when [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]x=\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. In other words, \u201cinsulated ends\" means that the boundary conditions are  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{\\text{insulated ends:}}} \\qquad \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial x}(0,t) = 0, \\qquad \\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial x}(\\pi ,t) = 0 \\qquad \\text{for all } t>0,[/mathjax]| (4.11)   ---|---      instead of [mathjaxinline]\\theta (0,t)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta (\\pi ,t)=0[/mathjaxinline]. So we need to solve the Heat Equation  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial \\theta }{\\partial t} = \\frac{\\partial ^2 \\theta }{\\partial x^2}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with the boundary conditions for insulated ends. Separation of variables [mathjaxinline]\\theta (x,t) = a(x) \\, b(t)[/mathjaxinline] leads to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\, a(x) \\qquad \\text{with } a^{\\prime }(0)=0 \\text{ and } a^{\\prime }(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.12)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{b}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\, b(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.13)      for a constant [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline]. Looking at the cases [mathjaxinline]\\lambda >0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda <0[/mathjaxinline], we find that  [mathjax]\\lambda = -n^2 \\quad \\text{ and } \\quad a(x) = \\cos nx \\text{ (times a scalar)}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is one of [mathjaxinline]0,1,2,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline]. (This time [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] starts at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]\\cos 0x[/mathjaxinline] is a nonzero function.) For each such [mathjaxinline]a(x)[/mathjaxinline], the corresponding [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]b(t) = e^{-n^2 t}[/mathjaxinline] (times a scalar), and the normal mode is  [mathjax]\\theta _n(x,t) = e^{-n^2 t} \\cos nx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The case [mathjaxinline]n=0[/mathjaxinline] is the constant function [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], so the general solution is  [mathjax]\\theta (x,t) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + a_1 e^{-t} \\cos x + a_2 e^{-4t} \\cos 2x + a_3 e^{-9t} \\cos 3x + \\dotsb .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Finally, we bring back the initial condition: substitute [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] and use the initial condition on the left to get  [mathjax]\\theta (x,0) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + a_1 \\cos x + a_2 \\cos 2x + a_3 \\cos 3x + \\dotsb[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for all [mathjaxinline]x \\in (0,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline].  Insulated ends", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Insulated ends"}

{"pageid": 125, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab8", "text": "**Example problem** Suppose that [mathjaxinline]c=1[/mathjaxinline], that the initial position is [mathjaxinline]I(x)[/mathjaxinline], and that the initial velocity is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. What does the wave look like?  **Solution:** The initial conditions [mathjaxinline]u(x,0) = I(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)=0[/mathjaxinline] become  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x) + g(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -f'(x) + g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The second equation says that [mathjaxinline]g(x) = f(x) + C[/mathjaxinline] for some constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline], and we can adjust [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] by constants to assume that [mathjaxinline]C=0[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]f(x) = I(x)/2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g(x)=I(x)/2[/mathjaxinline]. So the wave  [mathjax]u(x,t) = I(x-t)/2 + I(x+t)/2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      consists of two equal waveforms, one traveling to the right and one traveling to the left.  You can observe the wave an initial pulse of zero velocity splits into two half amplitude pulses traveling in opposite directions in the following demo video created by [TSG@MIT Physics](http://tsgphysics.mit.edu).  Example, d'Alembert", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab8-text3.html", "title": "Example, d'Alembert"}

{"pageid": 126, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab6", "text": "**Remark 6.1** If the ODE had been  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 36 x = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then all solutions would have been periodic, because [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t)[/mathjaxinline] has no [mathjaxinline]\\sin 6t[/mathjaxinline] term in its Fourier series.  In general, for a periodic function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], the ODE [mathjaxinline]P(D) x = f(t)[/mathjaxinline] has a periodic solution if and only if for each term [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] appearing with a nonzero coefficient in the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], the number [mathjaxinline]i\\omega[/mathjaxinline] is not a root of [mathjaxinline]P(r)[/mathjaxinline].  Pure Resonance", "filename": "solveodes-tab6-text2.html", "title": "Pure Resonance"}
