{"pageid": 130, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@introtofourier/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@introtofourier-tab6", "text": "Fourier's theorem (from the previous page) tells us that [mathjaxinline]\\\\{ 1, \\cos t, \\cos 2t, \\cos 3t, \\ldots , \\sin t, \\sin 2t, \\sin 3t, \\ldots \\quad \\\\}[/mathjaxinline] is a basis. So \"every\" [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic function can be represented as a Fourier series. The other incredibly useful property is that they are **orthogonal** . Orthogonality is what helps us answer our question on finding formulas for the Fourier coefficients.  **Question 6.4** Is [mathjaxinline]\\\\{ 1, \\cos t, \\cos 2t, \\cos 3t, \\ldots , \\sin t, \\sin 2t, \\sin 3t, \\ldots \\quad \\\\}[/mathjaxinline] an ortho ** _normal_** basis for all [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]-periodic functions, which can be represented by a Fourier series?  ###  Answer  No, since [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\langle 1,1 \\rangle = \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi 1 \\, dt = 2\\pi \\ne 1[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 6.5**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\langle \\sin t,\\sin t \\rangle[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi \\sin ^2 t\\, dt = \\; {\\color{orange}{?}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\langle \\cos t,\\cos t \\rangle[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi \\cos ^2 t\\, dt = \\; {\\color{orange}{?}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Since [mathjaxinline]\\cos t[/mathjaxinline] is just a shift of [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline], the answers are going to be the same. Also, the two answers add up to  [mathjax]\\int _{-\\pi }^\\pi \\underbrace{(\\sin ^2 t + \\cos ^2 t)}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{this is }1}} } \\, dt = 2\\pi ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so each is [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  The same idea works to show that  [mathjax]\\boxed {\\langle \\cos nt,\\cos nt \\rangle = \\pi } \\qquad \\text{and}\\qquad \\boxed {\\langle \\sin nt,\\sin nt \\rangle = \\pi }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for each positive integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].  Orthogonality", "filename": "introtofourier-tab6-text2.html", "title": "Orthogonality"}

{"pageid": 131, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab11", "text": "Suppose that [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is a piecewise differentiable periodic function, and that [mathjaxinline]\\, F\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline]. (If [mathjaxinline]\\, f \\,[/mathjaxinline] has jump discontinuities, one can still define [mathjaxinline]\\, F(t) \\colon =\\int _0^t f(\\tau ) \\, d\\tau + C \\,[/mathjaxinline], but at the jump discontinuities [mathjaxinline]\\, F\\,[/mathjaxinline] will be only continuous, not differentiable.)  The function [mathjaxinline]\\, F\\,[/mathjaxinline] might not be periodic. For example, if [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a function of period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]f(t) \\colon =\\begin{cases} 2, & \\textrm{ if } 0<t<1, \\\\\\ -1 & \\textrm{ if } -1<t<0, \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then [mathjaxinline]F(t)[/mathjaxinline] creeps upward over time.  ![Plot of the antiderivative of the function above](/static/images/antiderivative.svg)  An even easier example: if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) = 1 \\,[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, F(t) = t+C \\,[/mathjaxinline] for some [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\, F(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is not periodic.  But if the constant term [mathjaxinline]a_0/2[/mathjaxinline] in the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, F \\,[/mathjaxinline] **is** periodic, and its Fourier series can be obtained by taking the simplest antiderivative of each cosine and sine term, and adding an overall [mathjaxinline]+C[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] is the average value of [mathjaxinline]\\, F\\,[/mathjaxinline].  **Problem 11.1** Let [mathjaxinline]\\, T(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] be the triangle wave of period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and amplitude 1: so that [mathjaxinline]T(t) = |t|[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]-1 \\le t \\le 1[/mathjaxinline]. Find the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]T(t)[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** We could use the Fourier coefficient formula. But instead, notice that [mathjaxinline]T(t)[/mathjaxinline] has slope [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline](-1,0)[/mathjaxinline] and slope [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline](0,1)[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]T(t)[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of the period [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] square wave  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Sq}(\\pi t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1 \\text{odd}} \\frac{4}{n \\pi } \\sin n \\pi t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Taking an antiderivative termwise (and using that the average value of [mathjaxinline]T(t)[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]1/2[/mathjaxinline]) gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle T(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{2} + \\sum _{n \\ge 1 \\text{odd}} \\frac{4}{n \\pi } \\left( \\frac{-\\cos n \\pi t}{n \\pi } \\right)[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{2} - \\sum _{n \\ge 1 \\text{odd}} \\frac{4}{n^2 \\pi ^2} \\cos n \\pi t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Warning:** If a periodic function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is not continuous, it will not be an antiderivative of any piecewise differentiable function, so you cannot find the Fourier series of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] by integration.  **Remark 11.2** The Fourier series for a function with discontinuities can (formally) be differentiated term by term, but **the result will not converge.** For example, the term-wise derivative of the Fourier series for [mathjaxinline]Sq(t)[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{4}{\\pi } \\sum _{n \\text{ odd}} \\cos (nt).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This does not converge anywhere (since the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]th term does not even vanish as [mathjaxinline]n \\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline]). However, note that it is possible to make sense of this series, and of the anti-derivative of the square wave function, in terms of Dirac's delta functions and the theory of distributions \u2014 seen in more advanced courses than this one.  Antiderivative of a Fourier series", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Antiderivative of a Fourier series"}

{"pageid": 132, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation3_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation3_for_edx-tab1", "text": "You can check your work on the problem above by instead computing the Fourier coefficients for the function as having period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] rather than period [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  Hint", "filename": "recitation3_for_edx-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Hint"}

{"pageid": 133, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@28_heatequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@28_heatequation-tab10", "text": "The equation  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\alpha \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}, \\qquad 0 < x < L, \\, \\, t>0[/mathjax]| (4.14)   ---|---      was first introduced as a partial differential equation that describes the flow of heat in a rod. This equation can be used to model much more than heat flow, however, and appears across many fields in science and engineering. In the most general sense, equations of the above form are known as **Diffusion Equations.**  Diffusion Equations are used to model the \u201cspreading out\" of chemical species, biological cells, fluid vortices, and even people in a crowd. This all comes from the fact that the assumptions made when deriving the equation for heat are actual very simple assumptions based on the conservation of some quantity and the desire of that quantity to spread out in a simple way. We'll go through a problem that models the spreading of some chemical molecule along the length of a pipe. Such a model would be useful when designing a chemical reactor, an industrial device for synthesizing important chemicals from other more available inputs.  **The physics for modeling concentrations in mixtures.**  ![A pipe of length L and cross sectional area A with gas diffused in a liquid](/static/images/pipe1.svg)  Imagine a pipe filled with carbonated water. In this fluid, the carbon dioxide, or [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline], has a concentration which varies along the length of the pipe. (Assume the length of the pipe is very large compared to its diameter; this lets us ignore the variations in concentration in the radial direction of the pipe.) The [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] will \u201cdiffuse\" through the pipe as it randomly moves about, tending to spread out from areas of high concentration to low concentration. We'll list some of the important quantities for the model below. Note the similarities to the model used for heat transfer in a rod:  [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] |  length of the pipe   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] |  cross sectional area of the inside of the pipe   [mathjaxinline]u_0[/mathjaxinline] |  initial concentration of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] in the pipe   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  position along the length of the pipe   [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] |  the concentration of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] at a given point in the pipe at a given time, in terms of mass   [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] mass flux at a given point in the pipe at a given time      Note that these variables are all directly analogous to those used in the heat formulation. In addition, we have 2 basic laws that guide us with the model.    1. **Conservation of Mass** The total amount of carbon dioxide in the pipe is fixed\u2013none is leaving or being created. This means that if the mass is changing in any small segment of pipe, this must occur because [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] is flowing into or out of the region.     2. **Fick's Law of Mass Transfer** The idea is that [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] moves from regions of high concentration to regions of low concentration.   The equations that describe these two laws combine together (see below) to form the diffusion equation for concentration transfer:  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\alpha \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjax]| (4.15)   ---|---      ###  Putting it together to get the diffusion equation    1.  **Conservation of Mass:** The change in the total mass of chemical in any region equals the net mass flowing into or out of that region. (We assume that no [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] being created through reactions\u2014like active yeast cultures which produce [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] in beer.)   Concentration [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is a density, and therefore the units are [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{mass}/\\mathrm{volume}[/mathjaxinline], which is equivalent to [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{mass}/\\mathrm{length}^3[/mathjaxinline]. Consider a small slice of pipe with cross sectional area [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and length [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline]. The volume of this slice is [mathjaxinline]A\\Delta x,[/mathjaxinline] and the mass of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] inside is approximately [mathjaxinline]u(x) A\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline].  How does this mass change in a small amount of time [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline]? The only way for the mass to change in our small volume is by diffusing in through either of the two ends. The diffusion through either end is called flux. Flux, in this case [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] flux density, has units of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{mass}/[\\mathrm{time}\\cdot \\mathrm{length}^2][/mathjaxinline]. We can write the change in the [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] mass in a small volume [mathjaxinline]A\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] that occurs in a short time [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] as  [mathjax](u(x,t+\\Delta t)-u(x,t)) A\\Delta x = A\\Delta t(q(x,t)-q(x+\\Delta x,t))[/mathjax]| (4.16)   ---|---      The sign on the [mathjaxinline]q(x+\\Delta x,t)[/mathjaxinline] term is negative because [mathjaxinline]Aq(x+\\Delta x,t)\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] is the [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] mass passing to the right, out of the small [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] length over a small time interval [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline], while the flux on the left side is bringing new mass in. Note that Dividing by [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] we get  [mathjax]A\\frac{u(x,t+\\Delta t)-u(x,t)}{\\Delta t} = -A\\frac{q(x+\\Delta x,t)-q(x,t)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjax]| (4.17)   ---|---      We can take the limit as both [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] go to zero and divide through by [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] to get a relationship between the change in concentration and the change in flux:  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = -\\frac{\\partial q}{\\partial x}.[/mathjax]| (4.18)   ---|---     2.  **Fick's Law of Mass Transfer:** Analogous to Fourier's law of heat transfer, Fick's law of Mass transfer says that the flux between two points is proportional to the difference in concentration between the two points, with the appropriate sign so that the flow is from higher to lower concentration. We also note that it states that the flow between two points is inversely proportional to the distance between the points. This makes intuitive sense, as a small difference in concentration is more likely to generate a greater flux when the difference is over a short distance compared to a longer one. If we imagine two points along our pipe, [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x+\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline], then the [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CO} _{2}[/mathjaxinline] concentration at these points will be [mathjaxinline]u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u(x+\\Delta x,t)[/mathjaxinline], respectively. We can write Fick's Law of Mass Transfer as   [mathjax]q \\propto - \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}[/mathjax]| (4.19)   ---|---      We can make this an equality by adding the \u201cDiffusion Constant\" [mathjaxinline]\\alpha >0[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjax]q = -\\alpha \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}[/mathjax]| (4.20)   ---|---      Why is there a negative sign on the right of the expression above? We want [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] to be positive whenever we have a flux to the right, which means that [mathjaxinline]u(x+\\Delta x,t) <u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] (and we assume [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x > 0[/mathjaxinline]).Thus we have a negative sign in the above relation.  With the above two laws each giving an equation in terms of [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline], we can plug the second equation into the first to get a partial differential equation for just [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] as  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}=\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial x}\\left(\\alpha \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}\\right)[/mathjax]| (4.21)   ---|---      In the simplest cases, [mathjaxinline]\\alpha[/mathjaxinline] will be a constant, which simplifies the above equation to the most familiar form of the Diffusion Equation:  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\alpha \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}[/mathjax]| (4.22)   ---|---       **Note:** In some cases, [mathjaxinline]\\alpha[/mathjaxinline] may vary with [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] (such as a non-homogenous material where it is easier for cells to move in one region vs. another) and this changes the form of the equation. We will just assume [mathjaxinline]\\alpha[/mathjaxinline] is a constant, and thus get the familiar Diffusion Equation.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The physics", "filename": "28_heatequation-tab10-text1.html", "title": "The physics"}

{"pageid": 134, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab12", "text": "Here we will look at a different set up. We will have a horizontal beam, that is pinned at the left end, and pinned on a roller on the right end, where an axial load is applied. This is more to the case of the vertical beam that we saw first because the force is applied in the direction along the axis of the beam.  ![A horizontal beam pinned at the left end, and pinned on roller at right end.](/static/images/beam-8a.svg)  Here, we derive the maximum axial load [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] that can be applied to a beam before it begins to buckle. This problem was first solved by Leonhard Euler, and the value is often called _Euler's critical load_.  In order to solve this problem, we use the differential equation (with quadratic effect)  [mathjax]\\frac{d^4v}{dx^4}+k^2\\frac{d^2v}{dx^2} = 0, \\quad \\text{where }\\quad k^2 = \\frac{P}{EI},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline] is the vertical deflection of the beam away from the undeformed state, [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] is the axial load applied to the beam, and we have introduced the parameter [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] to simplify the notation.  The boundary conditions for a beam that is pinned at both ends are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle v(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0, v(L)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2}(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0, \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2}(L)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The differential equation is linear with constant coefficients. Therefore the solutions are exponentials of the form [mathjaxinline]v(x)= e^{\\lambda x}[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is a root of the characteristic equation  [mathjax]\\lambda ^4 + k^2\\lambda ^2 = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which has 4 roots, [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline] with multiplicity 2, and [mathjaxinline]\\lambda = \\pm ik[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the general solution takes the form  [mathjax]v(x) = A + Bx +C\\sin (kx) + D\\cos (kx),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for constants [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline], which must be determined by the boundary conditions in terms of the fixed constants [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline].  Plugging in the boundary conditions we get the following four equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A+B0+C\\sin (0)+ D\\cos (0) = A+D[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v(L) = 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A+BL+C\\sin (kL)+ D\\cos (kL)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2}(0)= 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k^2C\\sin (0)-k^2D\\cos (0) = -k^2D[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2v}{dx^2}(L)= 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k^2C\\sin (kL)-k^2D\\cos (kL)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The third equations tells us that [mathjaxinline]D=0[/mathjaxinline]. The first equation tells us that [mathjaxinline]A=0[/mathjaxinline]. This reduces our second and fourth equations to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle BL+C\\sin (kL)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k^2C\\sin (kL)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The second of these two tells us that [mathjaxinline]k^2C\\sin (kL)=0[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]k^2>0[/mathjaxinline], we know that [mathjaxinline]C\\sin (kL)=0[/mathjaxinline]. This fact along with the first equation tells us that [mathjaxinline]B=0[/mathjaxinline]. The fact that [mathjaxinline]C\\sin (kL)=0[/mathjaxinline] also means that either [mathjaxinline]C=0[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\sin (kL)=0[/mathjaxinline].  When [mathjaxinline]C=0[/mathjaxinline], we get the trivial solution that [mathjaxinline]v(x)=0[/mathjaxinline], and there is no vertical displacement. The second factor [mathjaxinline]\\sin (kL)[/mathjaxinline] is zero when [mathjaxinline]kL = n\\pi[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]n=1,2,3,\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline]. The smallest such value is when [mathjaxinline]k = \\pi /L[/mathjaxinline]. In this case, since [mathjaxinline]k^2 = \\frac{P}{EI}[/mathjaxinline], this implies that [mathjaxinline]P = EI\\pi ^2/L^2[/mathjaxinline]. When [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] reaches this critical value, the differential equation has infinitely many solutions of the form  [mathjax]v(x) = C\\sin (kx),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the amplitude [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] can be any number. Hence the amount of vertical displacement cannot be determined from this model. Our model is a linear theory, and is only valid when the bending of the beam is small.  This critical value of [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] is known as Euler's critical load. This value is determined by the boundary conditions, which you will see in the problems that follow.  The text", "filename": "bvp-tab12-text1.html", "title": "The text"}

{"pageid": 135, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab5", "text": "There are 6 categories of graded problems in 18.03Fx: Lecture exercises, MATLAB Recitation problems, the Laboratory, Part A Homework, Part B Homework, and the Exam.    * **6 Lecture exercises** These are the problems that are interspersed through the lecture content. These problems count for 10% of your grade.   These problems will be used to motivate theory, practice concepts, and review material from previous lectures. You are graded on these problems. This is where you will do the majority of your learning. We encourage you to make mistakes and learn from them!    * **6 Recitations** Each lecture has a corresponding recitation. These recitations involve a mixture of structured examples and MATLAB problems. These problems all allow an infinite number of attempts to complete. Failed attempts will not affect the final grade if the final attempt is correct. The entries of these answer boxes counts towards 10% of your grade.   At MIT, recitations are group work sessions led by a teaching assistant. We are hoping to create a similar collaborative learning environment on the forum. The skills you build in recitation can help you on the part B homework. You are free to discuss the solutions to these problems on the forum before the due date! In fact, we will not reveal solutions to these problems, so to ensure that you have understood these problems, please take the opportunity to discuss and learn from each other.    * **1 Laboratory** Unit 1 has a laboratory on the Discrete Fourier Transform and Signal Processing. This is an opportunity to take the ideas we have been learning and apply them to a real world context using MATLAB. This lab counts for 5% of your total grade.     * **3 Part A Homework** Each unit has 1 Part A Homework assignment, which gives you an opportunity to practice what you learned. These problems count for 10% of your total grade.   Wait until the end of the unit to attempt these problems. These problems help you identify the concepts that you have forgotten, and aid in long-term retention. These problems are mostly mechanical\u2013asking you to practice methods, and techniques learned in each unit. Each problem typically tests knowledge from only one section in a unit. (We won't necessarily tell you which one though!)    * **3 Part B Homework** Each unit has 1 Part B Homework assignment. The part B homework counts for 20% of your total grade.   The problems on this homework combine ideas from all of the sequences in the unit. These problems are mostly in the form of word problems which ask you to apply the methods learned to new scenarios.    * **1 Exam** The exam is the culmination of your learning, and will account for 45% of your grade. {"pageid": 136, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation4_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation4_for_edx-tab4", "text": "### Putting it all together  Putting what you discovered in the previous exercises, we can write the differential equation  [mathjax]\\frac{d^4v}{dx^4} = \\frac{q(x)}{EI}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as a linear system as follows:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} * & * & 0 & 0 & & 0 \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\\\*& * & 0 & 0 & & 0 \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & 0 & \\cdots & 0\\\\\\ 0 & \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & \\cdots & 0\\\\\\ & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\ddots & & \\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & \\circ & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 0 & * & * & * \\\\\\ 0 & \\cdots & 0 & 0 & * & * & * \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\\\\\ v_2 \\\\\\ v_3 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ v_{N-2} \\\\\\ v_{N-1} \\\\\\ v_N \\end{pmatrix} = \\frac{\\Delta x^4}{EI} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ q(x_3) \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ q(x_{N-2}) \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the rows of [mathjaxinline]*[/mathjaxinline] correspond to the boundary conditions, and the rows of [mathjaxinline]\\circ[/mathjaxinline] correspond to the fourth derivative.  Putting it all together", "filename": "recitation4_for_edx-tab4-text2.html", "title": "Putting it all together"}

{"pageid": 137, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab5", "text": "To specify a unique solution, we need two initial conditions: not only the initial position [mathjaxinline]u(x,0)[/mathjaxinline], but also the initial velocity [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)[/mathjaxinline], at each position of the string. (That **two** initial conditions are needed is related to the fact that the PDE is **second** -order in the [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] variable.)  For a plucked string, it is reasonable to assume that the initial velocity is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], so one initial condition is [mathjaxinline]\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)=0[/mathjaxinline]. What condition does this impose on the [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_n[/mathjaxinline]? Well, for the general solution above,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1} -n a_n \\sin (nt) \\sin (nx) + \\sum _{n \\ge 1} n b_n \\cos (nt) \\sin (nx)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}(x,0)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{n \\ge 1} n b_n \\sin (nx),[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so the initial condition says that [mathjaxinline]b_n=0[/mathjaxinline] for every [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]; in other words,  [mathjax]u(x,t) = \\sum _{n \\ge 1} a_n \\cos (nt) \\sin (nx).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If we also knew the initial position [mathjaxinline]u(x,0)[/mathjaxinline], we could solve for the [mathjaxinline]a_n[/mathjaxinline] by extending to an odd, period [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and using the Fourier coefficient formula.  **Wave equation mathlet**  The first few coefficients are the amplitudes of the \u201charmonics\" in the Wave Equation Mathlet.  Initial conditions", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Initial conditions"}

{"pageid": 138, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@29_waveequation/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@29_waveequation-tab8", "text": "### Traveling waves  D'Alembert figured out another way to write down solutions, in the case when [mathjaxinline]u(x,t)[/mathjaxinline] is defined for all real numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] instead of a finite interval [mathjaxinline]0 \\le x \\le L[/mathjaxinline]. Then, for any reasonable function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]u(x,t) \\colon =f(x-ct)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is a solution to the PDE, as shown by the following calculations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = (-c) f'(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f'(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = (-c)^2 f^{\\prime \\prime }(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f^{\\prime \\prime }(x-ct),[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so  [mathjax]\\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\frac{\\partial ^2 u}{\\partial x^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      What is the physical meaning of this solution? At [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline], we have [mathjaxinline]u(x,0) = f(x)[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the initial position. For any number [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], the position of the wave at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is the graph of [mathjaxinline]f(x-ct)[/mathjaxinline], which is the graph of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] shifted [mathjaxinline]ct[/mathjaxinline] units to the right. Thus the wave travels at **constant speed** [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] to the right, maintaining its shape.  The function [mathjaxinline]u(x,t) \\colon =g(x+ct)[/mathjaxinline] (for any reasonable function [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline]) is a solution too, a wave moving to the left. It turns out that the general solution is a superposition  [mathjax]\\displaystyle u(x,t) = f(x-ct) + g(x+ct).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      There is a tiny bit of redundancy: one can add a constant to [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and subtract the same constant from [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] without changing [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline].  It is important to note that these solutions assume that the wave is defined for all [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. However, there are ways to extend these general solutions to the case of finite intervals with boundary conditions. This is why we are able to show demo videos of finite strings to see some of the phenomena described here.  **Remark 8.1** Note that the d'Alembert solution is what allows us to easily understand the coefficient [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{c}}[/mathjaxinline] in the PDE as being the **wave speed** .  Traveling waves", "filename": "29_waveequation-tab8-text2.html", "title": "Traveling waves"}

{"pageid": 139, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab12", "text": "### Footnote  Most modern keyboard instruments divide the octave into [mathjaxinline]12[/mathjaxinline] half-steps, each of which represents a frequency ratio of [mathjaxinline]2^{1/12}[/mathjaxinline]. This means that intervals on such an instrument are only approximations to the pure intervals corresponding to rational number ratios. For instance,    * a fifth on a piano consists of [mathjaxinline]7[/mathjaxinline] half-steps, for example C to G, hence a frequency ratio of [mathjaxinline]2^{7/12} \\approx 1.4983[/mathjaxinline], whereas a pure fifth corresponds to a ratio of [mathjaxinline]3/2 = 1.5[/mathjaxinline].     * a major third on a piano consists of [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline] half steps, for example C to E, hence a frequency ratio of [mathjaxinline]2^{4/12} \\approx 1.2599[/mathjaxinline], whereas a pure third corresponds to a ratio of [mathjaxinline]5/4 = 1.25[/mathjaxinline].     * a major fourth on a piano consists of [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] half steps, for example G to C, hence a frequency ratio of [mathjaxinline]2^{5/12} \\approx 1.3348[/mathjaxinline], whereas a pure fourth corresponds to a ratio of [mathjaxinline]4/3 = 1.333\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline].   (For reference, see the book _Temperament_ by Stuart Isacoff.)  **Question 12.1** Can you guess what note corresponds to [mathjaxinline]9\\nu[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer  As mentioned above, multiplying a frequency by [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] raises the pitch by an octave plus a fifth. Given that [mathjaxinline]3\\nu[/mathjaxinline] is the G above middle C, we go up an octave to the next G, and then up a fifth from there. This means that [mathjaxinline]9\\nu[/mathjaxinline] corresponds to the D a little over two octaves above middle C.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Footnote", "filename": "solveodes-tab12-text3.html", "title": "Footnote"}

{"pageid": 140, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@bvp/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@bvp-tab6", "text": "To describe a function [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline], one needs to give infinitely many numbers, namely its values at all the different input [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-values. Thus [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] is like a vector of infinite length.  The linear differential operator [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline] maps each function to a function, just as a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix defines a linear transformation mapping each vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] to another vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline]. Thus [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline] is like an [mathjaxinline]\\infty \\times \\infty[/mathjaxinline] matrix.  The ODE [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} v = \\lambda v[/mathjaxinline] (with boundary conditions) amounts to an infinite system of equations: the ODE consists of one equality of numbers at each [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] in the interval [mathjaxinline](0,\\pi )[/mathjaxinline], and boundary conditions are equalities at the endpoints. Thus the ODE with boundary conditions is like a system of equations [mathjaxinline]A \\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline]. Nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} v = \\lambda v[/mathjaxinline] exist only for special values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline], namely  [mathjax]\\lambda = -1, \\; -4, \\; -9, \\; \\ldots ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      just as [mathjaxinline]A \\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] has a nonzero solution [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] only for special values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline], namely the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline]. But the differential operator [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline] has infinitely many eigenvalues, as one would expect for an [mathjaxinline]\\infty \\times \\infty[/mathjaxinline] matrix.  The nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} v = \\lambda v[/mathjaxinline] satisfying the boundary conditions are called **eigenfunctions** , since they act like eigenvectors.  **Summary of the analogies:**   **Eigenvector Problem**|  **Eigenfunction Problem**   ---|---   vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  function [mathjaxinline]v(x)[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] |  the linear operator [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline]   eigenvalue-eigenvector problem |  boundary value problem   [mathjaxinline]A \\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} v = \\lambda v[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]0 < x < \\pi[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]v(0)=0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]v(\\pi )=0[/mathjaxinline]   no more than [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] |  eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-1,-4,-9,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline]   no more than [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] eigenvectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  eigenfunctions [mathjaxinline]v(x) = \\sin (\\sqrt{-\\lambda }x)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =-1,-4,-9,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline]  Analogy with eigenvalue-eigenvector problems", "filename": "bvp-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Analogy with eigenvalue-eigenvector problems"}

{"pageid": 141, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab2", "text": "Differential equations are the mathematical language we use to describe the world around us. Many phenomena are not modeled by differential equations, but by partial differential equations depending on more than one independent variable. In this course, we will use Fourier series methods to solve ODEs and separable partial differential equations (PDEs). You will learn how to describe any periodic function using Fourier series, and will be able to determine how resonance affects the behavior of systems with periodic input signals. This course will use MATLAB to assist computations.  In this course we will explore:    * How to process noisy sound files     * The way a beam bends in response to external forces     * How to design ovens to evenly heat large objects without burning the edges     * The motion of a violin string   Course Description", "filename": "ourcourse-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Course Description"}

{"pageid": 142, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab6", "text": "What happens if instead of considering the differential equation  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + 50 x = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      we change [mathjaxinline]50[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]49[/mathjaxinline]  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + {\\color{blue}{49}} x = \\frac{\\pi }{4} \\mathrm{Sq}(t)?[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Pure Resonance", "filename": "solveodes-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Pure Resonance"}

{"pageid": 144, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@DFTLab/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@DFTLab-tab7", "text": "### Review of series RLC circuits  Here is an image of a series RLC circuit.  ![A series RLC circuit, with power source on left, induction coil at top, resistor at right, and capacitor at bottom. Inside it is 3/4 of an arc with an arrow showing counterclockwise orientation of current.](/static/images/RLC.svg)    The diagram shows symbols for four standard electronic components:  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{R}}[/mathjaxinline] |  resistance of the resistor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{ohms}[/mathjaxinline])   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{L}}[/mathjaxinline] |  inductance of the inductor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{henries}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{C}}[/mathjaxinline] |  capacitance of the capacitor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{farads}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{V}}[/mathjaxinline] |  voltage source ([mathjaxinline]\\text{volts}[/mathjaxinline])      The quantities [mathjaxinline]\\, R,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]L,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, C\\,[/mathjaxinline] are constants while the voltage source [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] is a function of time.    We say that current [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{I(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] flows clockwise. Since it's a series circuit, the current through any of the wires is the same. The power source produces a voltage **increase** of [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{V(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] volts at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. This voltage increase may vary with time, and may be negative as well as positive.  The voltage drop across each component is determined by its relationship to the current flowing through it.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{inductor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{V_L(t)}} =L\\dot I(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.1)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{resistor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{V_R(t)}} =RI(t).[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.2)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{capacitor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C {\\color{blue}{\\dot{V}_C(t)}} = I(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.3)      In what follows, we will typically think of [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] as being determined by a sound signal. Depending on how we want to process the signal, we will consider the system response to be any one of the voltage drops across the various components in our circuit.  One of the interesting features of this system is that the differential equation describing the series circuit is the same for all three possible system responses, but the way the input signal shows up is different for all three.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L{\\color{blue}{\\ddot V_R}} +R{\\color{blue}{\\dot V_R}} +\\frac{1}{C}{\\color{blue}{V_R}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle R{\\color{orange}{\\dot V}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{V}_L}} +R{\\color{blue}{\\dot{V}_L}} _+\\frac{1}{C} {\\color{blue}{V_L}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L{\\color{orange}{\\ddot V}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{V}_C}} +R{\\color{blue}{\\dot{V}_C}} _+\\frac{1}{C} {\\color{blue}{V_C}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{C} {\\color{orange}{V}}[/mathjaxinline] | |      For now, imagine that our input signal [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a single sinusoid of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline]. (More general (sound) signals are a superposition of such functions, so this is an OK assumption.)  The system response is determined by the complex gain of the system. If [mathjaxinline]V(t) = \\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline], then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle V_R(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{iR\\omega }{(\\frac{1}{C} -L\\omega ^2)+iR\\omega }e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle V_L(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{-L\\omega ^2}{(\\frac{1}{C} -L\\omega ^2)+iR\\omega }e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle V_C(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{\\frac{1}{C}}{(\\frac{1}{C} -L\\omega ^2)+iR\\omega }e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |  RLC Circuits", "filename": "DFTLab-tab7-text2.html", "title": "RLC Circuits"}

{"pageid": 145, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@periodicfunctions/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@periodicfunctions-tab3", "text": "### How to understand partial sums of the Fourier series  Very roughly, the idea of the Fourier series of a function, such as [mathjaxinline]S(t)[/mathjaxinline], is that it is the closest possible sum of sines that approximate the function on the interval, and at each degree, it is the best.  In what sense is it the closest?  We might want to say that it is the closest possible at every point. This is not possible since at points of discontinuity this automatically fails. The next thought is that we might want to say that it is closest in that the area between the function and the sine term of frequency [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is as small as possible. This is more forgiving at discontinuities. Remarkably, there is a correct notion of closest, and it is the integral of the difference of the functions quantity squared that is minimized.  [mathjax]\\int (f(x)-g(x))^2 \\, dx[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (This is called the **root-mean-squared distance** between two functions.)  **Remark 3.1** Extending our analogy with vectors used in the introduction of scalar product, this new distance is (almost) the same as the usual distance for vectors: [mathjaxinline]|a-b|=\\sqrt{\\langle a-b,a-b \\rangle }[/mathjaxinline].  Approximations", "filename": "periodicfunctions-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Approximations"}

{"pageid": 146, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@sequential+block@solveodes/block-v1:MITx+18.03Fx+1T2023+type@vertical+block@solveodes-tab12", "text": "### How we hear  Your ear is capable of decomposing a sound wave into its Fourier components of different frequencies. Each frequency corresponds to a certain pitch. Increasing the frequency produces a higher pitch. More precisely, multiplying the frequency by a number greater than [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] increases the pitch by what in music theory is called an **interval** . For example, multiplying the frequency by [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] raises the pitch by an octave, and multiplying by [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] raises the pitch an octave plus a perfect fifth.  When an instrument plays a note, it is producing a periodic sound wave in which typically many of the Fourier coefficients are nonzero. In a general Fourier series, the combination of the first two non-constant terms ([mathjaxinline]a_1 \\cos t + b_1 \\sin t[/mathjaxinline], if the period is [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]) is a sinusoid of some frequency [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline], and the next combination (e.g., [mathjaxinline]a_2 \\cos 2t + b_2 \\sin 2t[/mathjaxinline]) has frequency [mathjaxinline]2\\nu[/mathjaxinline], and so on: the frequencies are the positive integer multiples of the lowest frequency [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline]. The note corresponding to the frequency [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline] is called the **fundamental** , and the notes corresponding to frequencies [mathjaxinline]2\\nu[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]3\\nu[/mathjaxinline], are called the **overtones** .  The musical staffs below show these for [mathjaxinline]\\nu \\approx 131 \\operatorname {Hz}[/mathjaxinline] (the C below middle C), with the integer multiplier shown at the top of the image.  ![Notes on a scale depicting the overtones.](/static/images/overtones.svg)  How we hear", "filename": "solveodes-tab12-text2.html", "title": "How we hear"}
